column168: 9-5-05 Reported to me at 12:30 PM PST.  Our driver said he came off the roadway slightly with one wheel and lost control of his rig and rolled over.  His truck hit a Swift truck as it went over.  No injuries to anyone at the scene.    State Troopers at the scene called in Protech Environmental.  We additionally called in HMHTTC to assist.  At that time I was told only about a gallon of material had leaked out.  The ocean container carried about 14 totes of UN1268 and 6 totes of a non-regulated material.    A second truck was dispatched to the scene and the material was transloaded into the other truck.  This moring I was told by Protech that a 285 gallon tote was empty, HMTTC said one tote was 2/3 empty.  Still unsure of exact amount.  None of the material went into the drainage system though.    The accident caused the 10 freeway to be shut down for about 5 hours.
column169: I'm told our driver was cited for speeding.  Obviously this is a driver error.  He is a relitively new driver for us (July 2005).  Checked his MVR that was ran before hiring, and he has one prior speeding in 2003.  MVR does not indicate whether it was in a car or truck.  Other than that the MVR is clean.     If we keep this driver will go through extensive training on speed and a ban from handling hazmat loads.     All Hz drivers go though additional training and probation before moving any Hz.  This driver made an error in judgement.

Skids with drums loaded on them were being unloaded. The forklift operator tilted one of the pallets too much and 2 drums that were not properly secured to the pallet slid off. The drums struck something sharp puncturing both drums and spill about half of inner contents from each. Drums were set on their sides to prevent further spillage. I contacted Haz-Mat One and they contracted a local vendor named Emergency Response Services to respond and clean up the spill.       Supplemental report sent for update of actual costs.
column169: The drums should have been secured to the pallet. This would have prevented the drums from sliding off of the pallet during unloading.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: Driver was unloading last compartment at station when flapper valve closed with approximately 500 gallons left on the truck.  According to original stick readings total amount should have fit so the driver assumed that the fill tank was vapor locked.  The driver attempted to release the pressure in the hose by re-connecting the drop fitting but forgot to shut off the product flow valves. When the driver disconnected the drop fitting with product valves open she lost control of the hose and gasoline ran out of the hose onto the ground.  She first tried to re-connect the fitting and then when back to the trailer to shut off the flow.  Approximately 290 gallons were released. The driver then contacted dispatch and response crews were notified immediately.
column169: This incident has been shared with our transportation staff and our customer partner to help us understand how to mitigate similar events in the future.  Company wide safety meetings have been conducted to re-iterate the importance of following established procedures. (double checks when connecting or dis-connecting)
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: The trailer was supposed to be a passover load for our North Little Rock, AR terminal meaning they were not going to open the doors and work the freight, only change drivers. A chemical smell was noticed so the trailer was opened. The terminal found skids of pails of paint were double stacked without adequate blocking and bracing. The top pallet shifted and the pails fell off. 4 pails had their lids damage or knocked loose causing the paint to spill out. The spilled material was cleaned and the freight was restacked onto new pallets.
column169: Proper blocking and bracing would have prevented this spill. This freight also should not have been double stacked to begin with in my opinion.

column168: On September 21, 2005 a shipment marked non hazardous waste, n-methyl pyrrolidone solution was shipped to our facility. Upon analysis, it was discovered that the material did not meet the parameters of our facilities' hazardous waste operating permit. In talking with the generator, they determined that the material contained potassium hydroxide.  The shipment consisted of 6- 55gallon drums. All 6 drums were shipped back to the generator on September 27, 2005 as UN3267 material.  The generator assisted in classifying the material for shipment. No material was released.
column169: none

column168: Driver was transferring product from cargo tank to customer storage tank.  According to the sight gauge on customer tank, there should have been plenty of room for the product in the tank.  The tank overflowed about 15 gallons and there was still about 115 gallons left in our cargo tank.  Overflow was caused by a malfunctioning sight gauge on the customer's tank.  Customer cleaned up the spill.
column169: Sight gauges on customer storage tanks need to be maintained and their accuracy verified.

column168: Driver had stopped at a truck stop for a break.  He smelled a substance and noticed a leak.  He called dispatch, and dispatch contacted Clean harbors Environmental Services. Clean harbors contacted and sent out a clean-up crew.  The Ne. State police Haz response team was called by the truck stop operator.  The local Fire Dept. arrived and the truck stop was evacuated until the exact nature of the substance was determined.  The driver had already diked the liquid to prevent further spreading.  The local emergency team taped off the area around the truck and trailer.  The Clean Harbors team arrived and investigated the trailer and determined the leaking drum and the substance.  After eviewing the drum's contents, air monitoring the re-entered the trailer tightened the bung and also the bung on 4 other drums.  They then cleanud the spilled liquid outside the trailer.  They determined the cause was the shipper failed to properly tighten the bungs on 5 drums.
column169: Better training and follow up before, during and after loading by shippers.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  Upon opening trailer at the USF Reddaway, Inc. facility in Colorado Springs, Colorado, a leak was discovered.  The area was isolated and emergency personnel were contacted.  The Colorado Springs Fire Department/Hazmat Team responded to the site.  The free product released to the trailer floor and dirt parking lot.  The Hazmat Team inspected the trailer and determined that one (1) tote bin had been leaking due to an unsecure valve.  The valve was tightened and the free product was contained in tank traps placed outside the trailer.  RMCAT Environmental Services of Denver, Colorado was dispatched to assist in the cleanup.  RMCAT Environmental Services neutralized the free product on the dirt lot and along the trailer floor.  RMCAT Environmental Services generated one (1) 55-gallon drum of neutralized cleanup debris, which was disposed of per local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be related to a loose valve, due to shipper error, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While traveling on Interstate 20 westbound in Cleburne County, Alabama, driver was involved in a vehicle accident, which caused the truck to overturn into the median just outside the Alabama/Georgia state line at milemarker 214.  The Alabama Department of Transportation and Georgia State Highway Patrol responded to assist in traffic control.  The westbound lanes of Interstate 20 were shut down until approximately 9:00AM, during containment measures and cleanup of the roadway.  The Cleburne County Sheriff's Department and Fire Department, Haralson County, Georgia Sheriff's Department, U.S. Environmental Protection Agency Region 4, and Alabama Department of Environmental Management responded to assess the site.  Solutia, Inc., the shipper of the product, also responded to assess the site and oversee cleanup activity.  Southern Waste Services of Birmingham, Alabama was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Southern Waste Services neutralized the free product, and transferred all remaining product from the damaged totes, into new totes provided by Solutia, Inc.  Southern Waste Services also excavated the impacted soil within the median, and containerized all spent soil and neutralized material.  Meter readings were taken, and pH levels were returned between 4.4 and 4.8.  Alabama Department of Environmental Management was satisfied with cleanup activity, and approved waste disposal.  All waste generated during cleanup was transported to Onyx Star Ridge Landfill for disposal per local, state, and federal regulations.  Site was backfilled and restored to preexisting condition.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and occurred due to a motor vehicle accident, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.

column168: On September 8, 2005, four potential transformers were delivered to Onyx Environemntal Services for transfer and transport to our Phoenix AZ facility. While in temporary storage/transfer, an inspection was completed and one transformer was found to be leaking dielectric fluid from a crack in a welded seam just below the transformer bushing. Approximately 1 pint of dielectric fluid containing 164 ppm PCB was released into secondary containment system. The released material was absorbed off the concrete and the area was decontaminated in accordance with the EPA double wash double rinse procedure. The remaining dielectric fluid was drained from the transformer and the dielectric, clean up residues and absorbents were containerized and shipped with the transformer for incineration.
column169: Since the transformer would not fit into a shipping container the current practice of shipping transformers in this manner will need to continue. To prevent releases to the environment the transformers should be transported and stored within a secondary containment system. The containment area in this instance prevented the release of the dielectric to environmental media.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column168: Driver was dropping loaded cargo tank in our yard.  When doing a post-trip inspection, he noticed some product dripped on sides of cargo tank.  Product was wiped up with a spill pad and product transferred to another trailer because it appeared there may have been a problem with a weld on the wash out cap.  The trailer was sent to maintenance to be checked out but no problem was found.  It's possible the washout cap was cross threaded.
column169: Washout caps need to be properly secured so no product can leak out. Drivers are trained in that procedure.

column168: The shipment was offered under a vessel sharing agreement to Hapag-Lloyd Container Line by CP Ships, on behalf of their shipper, for transport on the Hapag-Lloyd container vessel Tokyo Express from New York to Thamesport.    The shipment was declared as two items of hazardous material - Paint, Class 3, UN 1263, and Printing Ink Related Material, Class 3, UN 1210.      CP Ships advised Hapag-Lloyd after the vessel had sailed from New York, that the fright container in fact contained Methyl Ethyl Ketone, Class 3, UN 1193, instead of the Paint as originally declared.    The shipping papers that accompanied the freight container to the marine terminal did not reflect the correct hazardous material loaded in the container.    CP Ships subsequently provided corrected hazardous material shipping papers to Hapag-Lloyd.

Driver went to hook up to loaded cargo tank and noticed a little product had leaked from dome area.  He wiped up with spill pad and tightened everything up.  He drove around the yard a little to make sure it was okay and it still leaked a little by dome.  It appears to have been a bad gasket.  Problem was corrected and no further incident of spillage.
column169: Driver need to follow through on their training and make sure gaskets are checked thorougly before cargo tanks are loaded.

column168: Shipment arrived at Topeka terminal with several boxes stained. Branch Manager found what appeared to be forklift damage. He separated the deliverable inner containers from the contaminated ones and placed the contaminated and damaged containers into a recovery drum for disposal. The good product was delivered.

column168: Thirty-three hundred (3300) gallons of diesel fuel were loaded into ExxonMobil fuel truck # 1938. The truck has the fuel capacity of thirty four hundred (3400) gallons. The truck was loaded at Lard Oil in Denham Springs La.  The spill of diesel fuel was at the bottom of the Interstate-110 Chippewa Street exit ramp and again a couple of hundred yards away at the Chippewa and Scenic Highway intersection, for a total of two (2) gallons. The spill was immediately cleaned up in both areas by ExxonMobil work crews with no further incidents.  The spill came from the top loading hatch which is located directly on top of the truck.
column169: The truck was taken out of service and sent to Slades Industrial Services Inc. to be checked for defects and repaired. The lid on the loading hatch was found to be defective due to a broken hatch lid tightness adjuster. The hatch lid was replaced with a new one. An additional safety feature was added that will prevent the release of the truck's breaks unless all valves and vents are closed.

Driver and loader were engaged in loading product from railroad tank car to cargo tank trailer.  After loading, loader secured railroad tank car and driver secured cargo tank trailer.  Driver completed paperwork and proceeded to exit loading facility when product began spilling from manway of cargo tank.  Driver stopped and reported incident.  Fire Department, Oregon Department of Environmental Quality, and National Response Center called.  Shipper's environmental response contractor called. Public agencies and response contractor arrive on-scene.  Response contractor decontaminates cargo tank.  Cargo tank manway was not properly secured, which resulted in product escaping its packaging.  Driver secures manway, shipper inspects manway and driver is allowed to proceed to consignee.
column169: Operating procedures changed to require loader to inspect securement of cargo tank before releasing vehicle after loading is completed.

column169: The major contributor to this crash and material release was poor deliverly directions provided to the driver causing him to get lost and travel the wrong road. column168: Driver had hoses hooked between cargo tank and customer storage tank.  Before driver opened valve on trailer to start the transfer of product to the storage tank, the customer opened their line.  Their tank is under a nitrogen blanket and pressure forced product from their tank, through our hose, through our pump and it came out the bottom bleeder valve on the trailer.  Less than 1/4 gallon spilled into the containment area before the customer could close their valve.  Bleeder valve appeared to be closed and the cap was on but the handle may have been a little loose making it appear to be closed.  Driver tightened everything up and finished the offload without incident.
column169: Driver should have rechecked valve manually instead of going by sight.  Also, a check valve on customer tank would have prevented backflow of product.

column168: Upon arrival to the consignee the truck was opened for off-loading.  The driver and consignee noted a small leak coming from one of the drums.  The driver immediatley called for a spill cleanup crew.  Upon arrival to the site, the cleanup crew over-packed the damaged drum.  Granular absorbent was put down on the free product on the floor of the trailer.  This material was then collected and placed in a five gallon poly drum for disposal.  The salvage drum and the five gallon drum were removed from the site for future disposal.  The duration of the entire release from discovery to cleanup was approximately 2.5 hours.
column169: A recommendation will be made to all shippers and drivers to inspect the load prior to initial shipment.  We also suggest the shipper speak with the drum manufacturer about quality and drum selection for this product.

column168: An operator on the previous day washed tanker #364.  On September 6, 2005 tanker #364 was spotted in the loading area to be filled with sodium hypochlorite (12.5% solution).  The loading operation began and approximately 10-15 minutes later, an employee noticed a release through an open valve.  He immediately closed the tanker unloading valve to stop flow out of tanker and notified management of the release.  The process line to the tanker was also closed.  Univar Contingency Plans were activated and responders notified. Spill occurred @ 9:30am on September 06, 2005 and duration of the release is estimated at approximately 10-15 minutes. An estimated total of 1,000 gallons (9,984 lbs) of bleach was released from the tanker.       About 100 gallons of the material released into an onsite storm water drainage ditch (land) that was dry. An earthen dike was dug at the ditch to prevent escape off-site.  All of the bleach and water in the ditch was collected via sump pump for management. The bleach in containment area was also captured and pumped into a storage tank.  Driveway and concrete storage pad was washed by Univar responders.  Clean water was introduced upstream of release to flush out residue.  All residue and water was pumped into Intermediate Bulk Containers and was neutralized.  Ohio EPA was onsite to monitor the response.
column169: Employee training completed by 9/27/2005 to ensure that all operators inspect valves to make sure they are closed on tankers before the loading process begins.      Employee training completed by 9/27/2005 that all drivers instructed to make sure that after a tanker is washed, all valves (internal and external) are closed to lessen the chance of a spill when it is loaded.    Video Surveillance System upgrade in progress to monitor loading process from multiple locations.

column168: Driver was transferring product from trailer to customer storage tank when he smelled an ammonia odor.  Driver shut off the compressor and investigated the odor.  Driver discovered that the relief valve on the trailer had lifted.  Driver attempted to get valve to reseat, but it would not reseat properly.  Customer asked driver to stop delivery.  Valve was replaced and the valve in question sent to a shop for analysis.  It was found that the o-ring gasket in the relief valve had become damaged when valve lifted and did not allow the valve to reseat.  Approximately 99 pounds of vapor was released (reporting program requires amount to be listed in liquid pounds).  No evacuations were made, no injuries reported, and no complaints of off-site odor were recorded.

column168: Two trucks met on an 18 foot wide road.  The right rear tire left the paved surface and traveled into the ditch parallel to the roadway.  The vehicle exited the ditch but rotated counterclockwise.  The vehicle then struck a bankon the opposite side and rolled over onto it's right side. About 5 gallons was caught in a bucket.  The released lasted for about 30 minutes at a drip.  Released product cleaned up and was properly disposed of.
column169: Additional training has been given on the legal requirements of using the seatbelts.  By not using seatbelts, it appears that driver was partially removed from seat at the time the wheel dropped off the road and from then on he was totally able to use corrective action.

Report states that Mission driver was making delivery of diesel to the store. Mission driver hooked up the drop gun to the hose and then connected the drop gun to the DS tank as to unload the diesel. MP Driver failed to hceck the drop gun for the "o" ring before connecting the drop gun to the tank. As there was no "o" ring to provide a seal, approx. 100-200 gallons of diesel was allowed to lead before the MP operator noticed the leak. Houston Fire Dept dispatched an engine to the scene. Fire Dept personnel used hose and water and pressure washed the spill area. They also used "microbaldes and was down the area -- Garner Environmental was contacted by MMPC and they placed absorbant pads.

The driver failed to completely close the valve on the discharge outlet before disconnecting the product off-loading line. When the driver started to disconnect the off-loading line there was a small amount of product that was released from the off-loading line due to the driver failing to completely close the discharge valve. The product was contained in the off-loading area.
column169: The driver was counseled on proper off-loading procedures.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While unloading, terminal personnel discovered two damaged, five gallon drums at the rear of the trailer.  Approximately 18.92 liters of free product were released.  The release was due to the load shifting in transit. BAX Global, Inc. personnel contained the free product with absorbents.  The Seattle Fire Department, King County International Airport Fire Department and Seattle Police Department were notified of the release and responded to assess the site.  The Seattle Fire Department and King County International Airport Fire Department completed the cleanup by placing the impacted absorbent materials and two damaged drums into one fifty gallon plastic recovery drum and one fifteen gallon plastic recovery drum.  Both recovery drums are being held at the facility for disposition.  No injuries were reported but three exposures were reported.  The three employees were treated by the Fire Department and did not seek any additional medical attention.  The material safety data sheet was requested.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and the result of the load shifting in transit no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.

column168: As per the drivers call: Driver called in after a freight check to report a leaking tote.  The tote had tipped over after a sudden stop.  The tote had not been chocked or braced.  Jevic Hazmat (JHM) called SRM Environmental to send a response crew to assist in the clean up.  The crew arrived on site and cleaned up the spilled material (20 gallons) and packed it into a drum.  The source of the leak, a cracked valve was sealed with epoxy.  JHM checked with several cartage houses in the area to see if we could use their space to upright the tote. They all refused.  A decision was made to send the trailer to Jevic’s West Chester, OH facility.    Once the trailer arrived at the facility, the tote began leaking again.  JHM called Environmental Enterprises (EE) to send a crew and transfer the remaining contents of the tote. The trailer was sent to EE to be decontaminated.  The trailer was returned to the West Chester, OH. And placed back into service.
column169: Loaders were counceled as to freight securement.

UPON THIS INVESTIGATION, THEY FOUND THIS PACKAGE TO CONTAIN MISCELLANEOUS PERSONAL ITEMS.  4 OUNCES LEAKED FROM THE NON REGULATED ITEMS.  HOWEVER, UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, THEY FOUND 1 X 7 OUNCE CAN OF SKINTIMATE MOISTURIZING SHAVE GEL MARKED CONTENTS UNDER PRESSURE.  AND 1 X 1 OUNCE GLASS BOTTLE OF BODY BY VICTORIA MARKED FLAMMABLE.  THESE DID NOT LEAK, BUT WERE NOT DECLARED AS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  THIS SHIPMENT ARRIVED INTO WILMINGTON VIA FLIGHT # 415, N791AX.  THE INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO THE GREAT LAKES REGION FEDERAL AVIATION ADMINISTRATION.  THIS SHIPMENT DID NOT HAVE MARKINGS/LABELS OR A SHIPPERS DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING IT TO INDICATE THAT THIS WAS A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  CLEAR OF SCENE: 0657.  THERE ARE PICTURES ON FILE IN THE HAZMAT OFFICE IN WILMINGTON, OHIO.

NOTE - Supplemental Report filed to correct location of incident.  While parked at a rest area after offloading his load, the Werner Enterprises driver observed a small amount of adhesive leaking onto the asphalt from the rear discharge line of the tanker.  Werner contacted American Compliance Technologies at approximately 1600 CST and requested dispatch of an Emergency Response Team to the site.  Mr. Dan McCarty of Environmental Solutions Inc. (ESI) mobilized to the site and observed approximately 1 gallon of material on the asphalt.  The adhesive was removed from the ground and placed in a 30-gallon poly drum.  The drum was placed under the leaking line.  The cam lock cap was removed from the discharge line and approximately 1 ½ gallons of product remaining in the discharge line drained into the drum.  The gasket was missing from the cam lock cap and the external discharge valve had not completely seated, possibly due to a buildup of adhesive.  The internal valve was holding.  ESI fabricated a gasket and resecured the external discharge valve and the cam lock cap.  The material collected in the drum was solidified and disposed.
column169: Drivers will be reminded to check all caps during placement for proper gaskets.  Valves will be inspected to ensure no buildup of products impairs valve function.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: Driver was transferring product from trailer to customer storage tank when he heard the relief valve on the tank lift prematurely at approximately 150 psi.  He stopped transferring product and turned the three-way valve to isolate the leaking relief valve.  Driver replaced the relief valve and completed his delivery.  Less than 10 pounds of vapor was estimated to have been released.  No evacuations were made, no injuries reported, and no complaints of off-site odor were recorded.

THE LEAK WAS DISCOVERED AT 12:30AM ON 9-13-05 WHEN A ROAD DRIVER PULLED INTO VITRAN (MILW) LOT AND HE NOTICED A LIQUID DRIPPING OUT OF THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  THE HOLE IN DRUM WAS ABOUT 1/2 INCH IN DIAMETER.  THE HOLE WAS CAUSED BECAUSE THE DRUM SLID BACKWARDS AGAINST THE DOOR AND BOLT IN THE DOOR PUNCTURED THE DRUM.  THE DRUM HAD LEAKED OUT FOR 6 HOURS BEFORE THE HAZ MAT CLEAN UP CREW ARRIVED.  NOTHING COULD BE DONE TO SLOW THE LEAK BECAUSE WERE ARE NOT EQUIPED TO HANDLE THIS PRODUCT DUE TO IT'S HEALTH HAZARD.
column169: BLOCK AND SECURE THE DRUM TO AVOID SHIFTING OF THE FREIGHT DURING TRANSIT.

column168: Driver had a delivery ticket to the home that has been delivered to before with the same instructions. The customer is a will call customer meaning they call for delivery, not automatic delivery. Customer neglected to state that they had a new gas heating system and that the oil tank had been removed. The fill and vent piping were not removed. The customer wanted the oil to go into the other tank that is at this home but did not provide a change in location. The driver started filling but heard no whistle. He heard the oil splashing around and thought it was going into the tank. He thought wrong. He was un-aware of this oops until the customer called our office.
column169: Our office provides training to all drivers. This includes our yearly seminar that is held to go over different things such as spill response, deliveries, driving, etc.

DRIVER WAS AT TRUCKERS INN, LOCATED IN FERNLEY, NEVADA WHEN HE BECAME AWARE OF A POTENTIAL PROBLEM WITH THE FIRE BLOCK VALVE.  THIS VALVE HAD RECENTLY BEEN REPAIRED, BUT THERE WAS INDICATION THAT A PROBLEM REMAINED.  THE DRIVER CONTACTED HIS TERMINAL MANAGER, WHO ADVISED HIM TO WAIT UNTIL HE COULD CALL THE CUSTOMER'S ENGINEER TO DETERMINE WHAT HE WOULD SUGGEST.  THERE WERE NO VISIBLE LEAKS AT THIS TIME.  OUR DRIVER ANTICIPATED THAT THERE MAYBE A PROBLEM UNLOADING AT THE CUSTOMER IN FRESNO, CALIFORNIA, SO HE WANTED TO SEE IF HE WOULD NEED TO TAKE THE TRAILER IN FOR REPAIRS.  HE DID NOT WANT TO ARRIVE AT THE CUSTOMER AND NOT BE ABLE TO DELIVER.  THE DRIVER CONTACTED THE CUSTOMER'S ENGINEER, WHO ADVISED THE DRIVER TO INSPECT AND REPAIR THE VALVE.  WHICH OUR DRIVER PROCEEDED TO DO.  DURING THE PROCEDURE OUR DRIVER NOTICED THAT THERE WAS PRESSURE AND TOLD THE ENGINEER, WHO TOLD HIM THAT THERE WASN'T MUCH, SO OUR DRIVER CONTINUED.  OUR DRIVER NOTICED LIQUID AND ADVISED THE ENGINEER.  THE ENGINEER STATED THAT THERE SHOULD NOT BE LIQUID THERE AS THIS IS A BALL VALVE.  OUR DRIVER CONTINUED AND THE STEM POPPED OFF FILLING THE AREA WITH LIQUID.  THE DRIVER BACKED AWAY THINKING IT WOUDL SLOW AND HE WOULD THEN BE ABLE TO PUT THE VALVE STEM BACK IN.  WHILE HE WAS STANDING BACK HE KNEW IT WAS NOT GOING TO STOP UNLESS HE WAS ABLE TO PUT THE VALVE STEM BACK IN PLACE AND AT THIS TIME A PERSON WORKING FOR THE TIRE REPAIR BUSINESS AT THIS LOCATIONS CAME FROM THE TRUCK STOP AND ASKED WHAT WAS HAPPENING AND ASKED IF HE SHOULD CALL THE FIRE DEPARTMENT.  THE DRIVER AGREED THAT HE SHOULD DO THAT.  WHEN THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED THE DRIVER MENTIONED SEVERAL TIMES TO THE FIRE DEPARTMENT THAT HE WOULD LIKE TO OPEN THE VALVE TO THE VENT STACK TO REDUCE THE PRESSURE SO HE COULD PUT THE VALVE BACK IN PLACE AND THE LEAK WOULD STOP.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT PROCEDURES WOULD NOT ALLOW HIM TO GO NEAR THE TRAILER.  WHEN HAD AN EMPTY TRAILER ON SITE AT APPROXIMATELY 8:30 PST TO TRANSFER THE PRODUCT.  THE WORSE CASE WAS TO VENT THE GAS FROM THE TRAILER INTO THE EMPTY TRAILER TO REDUCE THE PRESSURE SO WE COULD PUT THE VALVE BACK TOGETHER ON THE LIQUID SIDE.  FIRE DEPARTMENT PROCEDURES WOULD NOT ALLOW THIS TO BE DONE.  EVERYONE WAS MOVED BACK AWAY FROM THE EQUIPMENT.  THE EMERGENCY CREW MUST HAVE BEEN DISCUSSING AN ACTION PLAN AND APPROXIMATELY AN HOUR LATER THE FIREMEN WERE CHECKING THE AIR QUALITY, FIRST UPWIND AND PLACED CONES DOWN APPROXIMATELY 30 FEET FROM OUR EQUIPMENT.  THEY THEN WALKED DOWN WIND AND WERE APPROXIMATELY 50 FEET AWAY NEAR SOME PARKED CARS.  OUR DRIVER SAID THEY JUST GOT BEHIND THE PARKED CARS AND BENT DOWN AND ALL OF A SUDDEN HE NOTICED THE FLAME HEADING TOWARDS THE TRAILER.  EVERYONE WAS THEN TOLD TO LEAVE THE AREA.  IS IS OUR UNDERSTANDING THAT A SPARK WAS GENERATED BY ONE OF THE FIREMEN, WHICH RESULTED IN THE TRAILER CATCHING FIRE.  THE TRAILER BURNED FOR TWO FULL DAYS PRIOR TO THE PRODUCT BURNING OUT.  THE FLAMES WERE AT VALVE PORT WHERE THE STEM WAS MISSING AND
column169: DISCUSSIONS ARE BEING HELD WITH ALL DRIVERS TO REMIND THEM OF THE IMPORTANCE OF NOT ATTEMPTING TO MAKE ANY ROAD REPAIRS.  THE OWNER OF THE TRAILER IS INSPECTING ALL TRAILER OF LIKE MAKE AND MOBEL FOR THE INTEGRITY OF THE VALVE THAT WAS THE CAUSE OF THIS INCIDENT.

column169: WE HAVE MADE SPECIAL MENTION IN OUR TRAINING TO BE VERY CAUTIOUS AND AWARE OF ANY UST'S WITH TWO FILL INLETS.  DRIVERS ARE TO USE BOTH FILL INLETS IF POSSIBLE, IF NOT DRIVER ARE TO CHECK THE ONE NOT IN USE BEFORE UNLOADING.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 5:00 PM ON SEPTEMBER 7, 2005, A VAN TRAILER OPERATED BY CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES INC. (CHESI) EXPERIENCED A MINOR RELEASE OF HAZARDOUS WASTE FROM A NON-BULK PACKAGE.  PLEASE NOTE THAT AT THE TIME OF THE RELEASE, THE VEHICLE WAS PAKED WITHIN A TRANSPORTATION RELATED AREA LOCATED AT CHESI'S SERVICE CENTER LOCATED AT 4475 S. DORT HIGHWAY IN BURTON, MI.  FACILITY PERSONNEL, UPON DISCOVERING THE SUSPECTED RELEASE, SECURED THE VEHICLE TO PREVENT UNAUTHORIZED ACCESS, RETRIEVED ALL ASSOCIATED SHIPPING DOCUMENTATION AND MOBILIZED AN IN-HOUSE EMERGENGY RESPONSE CREW TO IDENTIFY THE SOURCE OF THE RELEASE AND TO TAKE ALL NECESSARY CORRECTIVE ACTIONS.  UPON REVIEW OF THE PAPERWORK, THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREW DONNED APPROPRIATE PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND ENTERED THE TRAILER.  AN INSPECTION OF THE NON-BULK PACKAGES IN THE TRAILER IDENITIFIED THAT A SINGLE 55 GALLON UN 1A2 CONTAINER OF A CLASS 8 LIQUID DEVELOPED A PINHOLE LEAK NEAR THE DRUM'S SEAM NEAR THE TOP OF THE CONTAINER.  THE RESPONSE CREW IMMEDIATELY USED A CHEMICALLY COMPATIBLE ABSORBANT MATERIAL TO CONTAIN APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF LIQUID THAT WAS RELEASED TO THE FLOOR OF THE CONTAINER AS WELL AS THE APPROXIMATELY 1 PINT OF MATERIAL THAT ACTUALLY DRIPPED FROM THE VAN TRAILER ONTO THE ASPHALT PARKING AREA.  THE CREW THEN PLACED THE LEAKING CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM.  AS A PRECAUTION THE 8 ADDITIONAL SIMILAR CONTAINERS WERE OVERPACKED FOR CONTINUING TRANSPORTATION.  ALL OF THE ABSORBENT MATERIAL USED TO CLEAN UP THE LEAK ALONG WITH ALL CONTAMINATED DISPOSABLE SAFETY EQUIPMENT AND CLOTHING WAS COLLECTED AND PLACED INTO APPROPRIATE DRUMS FOR DISPOSAL AT A FULLY LICENSED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY.
column169: OUR INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT THE CAUSE OF THIS INCIDENT CAN BE ATTRIBUTED TO THE USE OF AN UNLINED STEEL CONTAINER.  DUE TO THE ACIDIC NATURE OF THE WASTE STREAM AND THE SUBSEQUENT PROLONGED STORAGE OF THE MATERIAL DURING THE WASTE ACCUMULATION PERIOD, THE WEAKER PARTS OF THE CONTAINER FAILED.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS INCIDENT, THE SHIPPER OF THIS MATERIAL WILL BE REQUIRED TO CERTIFY THAT THE PROPER UN RATED SHIPPING CONTAINERS ARE USED THAT ARE COMPATIBLE WITH THE MATERIAL BEING SHIPPED.  IN ADDITION, REFRESHER TRAINING ON PROPER CONTAINER SELECTIONS, CLOSURE AND INSPECTION WILL BE PROVIDED AS PART OF ALL HAZ MAT EMPLOYEES' ONGOING TRAINING.

column168: THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO THE CARTON BEING ACCIDENTALLY RUN OVER BY A FORKLIFT.  THE ASSOCIATE WAS COVERED IN A SPRAY THAT EMITTED FROM THE CARTON WHEN IT WAS CRUSHED BY THE FORKLIFT TIRE.  THE ACID GOT IN THE ASSOCIATES EYES.  HE WASHED HIS EYES IN THE EYE WASH FOR 15-20 MIN AND WAS TAKEN TO THE ER.  AT THE HOSPITAL HE WAS TREATED AND RELEASED TO GO HOME WITH A DIRECTIVE TO GO TO THE COMPANY CLINIC THE NEXT DAY.  THE CLINIC GAVE HIM DIRECTION TO GO TO AN EYE DOCTOR.  THE EYE DOCTOR GAVE THE ASSOCIATE THE REST OF THE DAY AND THE NEXT DAY OFF FROM WORK.  THE ASSOCIATE LOST 16 HOURS OF WORK TIME, AND HAS RETURNED BACK TO WORK AS OF 9/22/2005.

column168: Railroad crew notified corporate office of an ammonia odor while performing a rail car switch.  Driver was dispatched to site to investigate.  Driver found a liquid valve spindle on a cargo tank that was slightly loose and a hydrostatic relief valve on the same cargo tank weeping.  Driver tightened the valve spindle, bled down the line and replaced the hydrostatic relief valve.  Less than a pound of product was estimated to have been released.  No evacuations were made, no injuries reported, and no complaints of off-site odor were recorded.

column168: BNSF SWITCH CREW SWITCHING IN RAILYARD REPORTED A PRODUCT VAPOR MIST FROM THE TOP OF RCRX 1746 DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS.  NO PRODUCT MIST WAS REPORTED REACHING THE GROUND AND IT WAS CONFINED TO THE TANK CAR SHELL.  MOVEMENT OF RCRX 1746 WAS IMMEDIATELY STOPPED AND IT WAS CORDONED OFF AT ITS LOCATION IN THE YARD TRACK.  CONSIGNEE RESPONDERS FOUND THE 165 PSI FRANGIBLE DISC HAD BLOWN AND IT WAS REPLACED IN KIND BY 0415 HRS. CDT, 9/14/05.  THE RESPONDERS ALSO NEUTRALIZED THE AREA AROUND THE SAFETY VENT THAT WAS IMPACTED BY THE VAPOR MIST.
column169: NO ADDITIONAL COMMENTS.

column168: FRA/CALIFORNIA PUC INSPECTOR IN BNSF RAILYARD OBSERVED PRODUCT EXPULSION FROM AROUND THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER ATOP NATX 50049 WHILE IT WAS BEING SWITCHED.  SWITCH MOVEMENT WAS STOPPED AND NATX 50049 WAS CAREFULLY ISOLATED IN THE RAILYARD.  PRODUCT SPILLAGE WAS PREDOMINANTLY ON THE TANK CARS SIDE SHELL, IN AND AROUND THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER.  FRA/PUC INSPECTOR FOUND THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER SEAL INTACT.  INSPECTION UNDER THE VALVE HOUSING COVER REVEALED THAT THE AIR LINE PIPE WAS WITHOUT ANY CLOSURE VALVE, FLANGE, CAP, OR PLUG.  A CAN WITH INTERIOR STUFFING WAS FOUND LYING WITHIN THE VALVE HOUSING AREA NEXT TO THE AIR LINE PIPING.  SHIPPER CONTRACT RESPONDERS APPLIED A THREADED ONE INCH BALL VALVE WITH CLOSURE PLUG ONTO THE THREADS OF AIR LINE PIPE, THUS CLOSING AND SECURING THIS OPEN ORIFICE BY 1010 HRS. PDT, 9/15/05.  BNSF MECHANICAL FOREMAN WIPED THE NON-EVAPORATED PRODUCT SPILLAGE FROM NATX 50049'S TANK CAR SHELL.
column169: ENSURE SHIPPER'S PRE-TRIP INSPECTION PROCESS IS FULLY IMPLEMENTED AND VALIDATED AS IT PERTAINS TO THE MECHANICAL FITNESS AND SECUREMENT OF ALL VALVES AND FITTINGS.

column168: BNSF LOCAL CREW SWITCHING IN RAILYARD REPORTED A PRODUCT SLOSH FROM THE MANWAY OF PSPX 23538 DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS.  NO RPODUCT WAS REPORTED REACHING THE GROUND AND IT WAS ONLY CONFINED TO THE TANK CAR SHELL.  PSPX 23538 WAS CAREFULLY ISOLATED IN THE RAILYARD AWAITING FURTHER INVESTIGATION INTO THE CAUSE OF THE PRODUCT EXPULSION.  NO PRODUCT WAS RELEASED WHEN PSPX 23538 WAS NOT MOVING.  SHIPPER CONTRACT RESPONDERS FOUND THE EIGHT MANWAY SECUREMENT BOLTS TOOL TIGHT, BUT NOT OVERLY TIGHTENED.  THE MANWAY GASKET WAS INSPECTED AND IT WAS CUT/SPLIT IN TWO PLACES AT OPPOSITE SIDES OF THE GASKET CIRCUMFERENCE.  A NEW GASKET WAS APPLIED AND THE MANWAY WAS SECURED BY 1800 HRS. CDT, 9/08/05.  ALL SPILLAGE ON THE TANK SHELL EVAPORATED.  RESPONDERS INDICATED THAT THE GASKET LIKELY SUCCUMBED TO AGE DETERIORATION.
column169: ENSURE SHIPPER'S PRE-TRIP INSPECTION PROCESS IS FULLY IMPLEMENTED AND VALIDATED AS IT RELATES TO THE MECHANICAL FITNESS AND SECUREMENT OF ALL VALVES AND FITTINGS.

column168: The shipment was offered under a vessel sharing agreement to Hapag-Lloyd Container Line as non hazardous material by P & O Nedlloyd Lines, on behalf of their shipper, for transport on the Hapag-Lloyd container vessel Northern Fortune from Miami, Florida to Cagliari, Italy.     P & O Nedlloyd advised Hapag-Lloyd after vessel had sailed from Miami that the shipment was not booked as hazardous materials, the shipping papers did not indicate the presence hazardous materials, and that the container was not placarded and/or marked.  P & O Nedlloyd subsequently provided corrected hazardous material shipping papers to Hapag-Lloyd.     Hapag-Lloyd advised the Master of the vessel of the undeclared hazardous materials onboard.

column168: Driver called in to terminal to report that a battery that was strapped to a pallet had tipped over in transit. He was close enough to his domiciled terminal for him to return. Once back it was discovered that the pallet that the battery was originally shipped out on was not strong enough to hold the weight of the battery and as a result broke consequently causing the battery to fall over. While trying to upright the battery back at the terminal some enclosed electrolyte leaked out in the process. The spilled material was neutralized and cleaned with absorbent. Tipped over battery was uprighted and placed on a heavier pallet and shipped to ultimate consignee without further incident.
column169: Shippers need to select proper skids and materials to support the weight of the shipments tendered during transit.
column172: Box, wood or fiberboard not specified

column168: When unloading freight material handler found a box in a shipment that was partially wet. There was no obvious reason why this box was wet, there was no noticeable action that contributed to this failure. The box was removed from the shipent and opened to investigate wetness. Upon opening the box it was discovered that one of the caps on an enclosed bottle had come off during transit thus contributing to the failure. The cap was put back on the bottle to prevent further leakage.
column169: Must make sure that inner containers are secure and properly sealed for transportion.

WE WERE TRANSFERING A LOAD FROM A VACUUM TANKER TO A BULK TRANSPORT TANKER.  DURING THIS TRANSFER (TOWARDS THE END) THE VACUUM WAS PUSHING MATERIAL ONTO THE BULK TANK TO FAST OR WITH TO MUCH PRESSURE.  MATERIAL WAS SENT OUT OF THE CENTER DOME AND INTO THE SPILL TRAY AROUND THE CENTER DOME.  MATERIAL LEAKED DOWN THE SIDE OF THE TANKER AND ONTO A CONTAINMENT PAD.  AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WAS CALLED TO CLEAN UP AFTER GUIDE 131 WAS REVIEWED.  MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP WITHIN 2-3 HRS OF INCIDENT.
column169: TRANSFER AT LOWER SPEED & PRESSURE.  TAKE MORE TIME AND STRESS THE DANGERS ANY TIME THIS IS DONE.

THE PACKAGING (31HA1 PORTABLE TANK) DID NOT FAIL.  IT WAS SECURELY LOADED IN A CLOSED SEMI-TRAILER WHEN THE SEMI-TRAILER ROLLED OVER ONTO ITS SIDE IN A TRAFFIC INCIDENT.  A MINIMAL AMOUNT OF THE MATERIAL SEEPED OUT OF THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE ON ONE OF THE THREE TOTES.  HOWEVER, NONE OF THE MATERIAL FOUND ITS WAY OUT OF THE TRAILER AND ON TO THE GROUND.  THE LEAKAGE OCCURRED OVER THE COURSE OF APPROXIMATELY 12 HOURS, AS THE TRAILER WAS DRAGGED OFF THE HIGHWAY AND TO THE SIDE OF THE ROADWAY TO FACILITATE UNLOADING AS WELL AS CLEARING THE BLOCKED LANE OF I-25 FOR TRAFFIC.  THE TOTES WERE INSPECTED AND RE-LOADED ONTO ANOTHER TRAILER WHERE THEY WERE FORWARDED ON TO THE CONSIGNEE FOR DELIVERY.
column169: DRIVER STATED HE HAD ATTEMPTED TO AVOID A COLLISION WITH AN ELK AS IT STRAYED ONTO THE N/B LANES OF I-25.  HIS ABRUPT EVASIVE MANUEVERS CAUSED HIS REAR TRAILER TO FLIP OVER, AND STILL THE ELK WAS HIT BY ANOTHER TRACTOR SEMI-TRAILER COMBINATION WITHIN SECONDS OF THE INCIDENT INVOLVING THE ROLL-OVER.  DRIVER SHOULD BE ONCE AGAIN REMINDED NOT TO ATTEMPT TO EXECUTE SEVERE EVASIVE MANUEVERS ON ANY VEHICLE AT FREEWAY SPEEDS AS SUCH MANEUVERS COMMONLY RESULT IN A VEHICLE OVERTURN.  WHEN THE VEHICLE INVOLVED IN AN OVERTURN IS A COMMERCIAL MOTOR VEHICLE (CMV) CONTAINING DOT REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, THE CONSEQUENCES ARE GREATER AND FAR-REACHING.  CONSIDERATION COULD BE GIVEN TO INCREASED WILD GAME PROTECTION, IN THE FORM OF MORE EFFECTIVE FENCING, TO PREVENT WILDLIFE FROM ENTERING MAJOR TRANSPORTATION ARTERIES.

WHILE FILLING THE AST, IT OVERFLOWED ALLOWING APPROX 900 GALLONS OF PRODUCT TO ESCAPE.  WE IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED PROPER AUTHORITIES AND CLEAN-UP CONTRACTOR MILLER ENVIRONMENTAL WHO CONTINUES TO HANDLE THE REMEDIATION EFFORTS.
column169: CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND EDUCATE DRIVERS ON PROPER UNLOADING PROCEDURES.  IF NOT 100% SURE LOAD WILL FIT, DO NOT MAKE DELIVERY.

column168: A CUSTOMER TRUCK ARRIVED FOR A LOAD OF PURIFIED ACID.  PRIOR TO LOADING, THE OPERATORS ROUTINELY PERFORM A BUCKET TEST TO MAKE SURE THAT THE PRODUCT IS NOT CONTAMINATED BY ANYTHING IN THE TANKER.  DURING THE BUCKET TEST, AN INTERNAL VALVE ON THE TANK LEAKED WHICH RESULTED IN THE 5-GALLON BUCKET USED FOR TESTING TO OVERFLOW.  THE INCIDENT OCCURRED OVER CONCRETE/BERMED AREA AND DID NOT RESULT IN ANY ACID REACHING SURFACE WATERS OR LEAVING THE PROPERTY.  AS SOON AS WAS PRACTICAL, THE EXTERNAL VALVE WAS MANUALLY SHUT.  AFTER THE VALVE WAS SECURED, THE TRUCK LEFT AND RETURNED WITH A DIFFERENT TANKER.  THE NEW TANKER WAS FILLED WITHOUT INCIDENT.  WHEN THE TANKER WAS RETURNED TO THE TERMINAL FOR INSPECTION AND REPAIR, A SMALL (3/8") STAINLESS STEEL HOOK WAS FOUND TO BE OBSTRUCTING THE OPERATION OF THE INTERNAL VALVE.  THE METAL ROD WAS REMOVED.  THE TANKER WAS TESTED AND RETURNED TO SERVICE.
column169: FURTHER INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT THE STAINLESS STEEL CURVED ROD WAS BROKEN OFF FROM THE LOADING ARM AT THE TRUCK LOADOUT WHEN THE SPOUT WAS LOWERED THROUGH THE MANWAY.  THE HOOK IS USED FOR HOLDING THE LOADING ARM CAP WHILE TRUCKS ARE BEING LOADED.  A NEW SMALLER HOOK WILL BE WELDED TO THE LOADING ARM WHICH WILL MINIMIZE THE LIKELIHOOD OF THIS TYPE OF SITUATION IN THE FUTURE.  IN ADDITION, THE BUCKET TEST PROCEDURE WILL BE MODIFIED TO USE LESS THAN 5 GALLONS OF PRODUCT, DECREASING THE LIKELIHOOD OF THE BUCKET RUNNING OVER DURING THE BUCKET TEST.

column168: A CUSTOMER SENT A TANKER IN TO PICK UP A 45,000 POUND LOAD OF DC-212S (CONTAINS DIETHANOLAMINE, AN ENVIRONMENTALLY HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE, AT 5 TO 6%.)  THE CUSTOMER HAD USED A BROKER TO BOOK THE LOAD.  THE BROKER SENT A 5000 GALLON TANKER TO PICK UP THE LOAD.  THE WAREHOUSE TECHNICIAN FILLED OUT THE INSPECTION SHEET BUT DID NOT LOOK AT THE VOLUME OF THE TANKER(IT IS NOT REQUIRED ON THE INSPECTION FORM.)  THE NORMAL TANKERS THAT ARE LOADED BY THE TECHNICIAN ARE 6800 TO 7000 GALLONS.  HE ASSUMED THIS WAS A STANDARD SIZE TANKER.  THE WAREHOUSE TECHNICIAN ATTEMPTED TO LOAD 45,000 # ONTO THE TRUCK PER THE CUSTOMER'S REQUEST.  THE DENSITY OF THE MATERIAL IS ONLY 8.16#/GAL.  THIS MEANT THAT THE TANKER WOULD ONLY HOLD APPROX. 40,000# BEFORE RUNNING OVER.  THE TECHNICIAN WAS USING THE OUTAGE ON THE TANK GUAGE TO DETERMINE THE PROPER AMOUNT LOADED, SO HE DID NOT DISCOVERED THAT THE TRAILER WOULD NOT HOLD THE MATERIAL UNTIL IT STARTED RUNNING OVER.  HE THEN HAD TO SHUT OFF THE PUMP AND CLOSE THE VALVES.  THE TRUCKS ARE LOADED ON A CONTAINED PAD SO THE SPILL DID NOT RESULT IN A RELEASE.  THE SUMP, WHICH DRAINS TO OUR ON-SITE WASTEWATER TREATMENT PLANT, WAS CLOSED AND THE MATERIAL WAS COLLECTED INTO TOTES FOR USE IN VESSEL CLEANING LATER.  THE MATERIAL HAS A VERY LOW VAPOR PRESSURE SO NONE WAS RELEASED TO THE AIR.  WATER WAS USED TO WASH OFF THE TRUCK PAD.  THE RINSE WATER WAS DRAINED TO OUR ON-SITE WASTE WATER TREATMENT FACILITY.
column169: WE WILL MODIFY THE PRE-LOADING CHECK LIST TO INCLUDE HAVING THE TECHNICIAN RECORD THE VOLUME OF THE TANKER.  FOR ANY TANKER LESS THAN 6800 GALLONS THE TECHNICIAN WILL HAVE TO CALCULATE THE WEIGHT IT WILL HOLD BY MULTIPLYING THE DENSITY OF THE MATERIAL BY THE VOLUME IN GALLONS OF THE TANKER.  THIS WOULD HAVE PREVENTED THIS INCIDENT.

column168: 9/22/05: AT APPROXIMATELY 1:30 PM, WHILE PERFORMING A ROUTINE COMPLIANCE INSPECTION AT CONRAILS BAYONNE, NJ YARD FACILITY, FRA HAZARDOUS MATERIALS INSPECTOR R.A. DEDOW NOTED TANK CAR NATX 301217, LOAD METHANOL(3, UN 1230, PG II, RQ) TO HAVE A LEAK ORIGINATING FROM THE CLOSED SYSTEM LIQUID LOADING/UNLOADING VALVE. MR. DEDOW NOTED THAT THE MATERIAL WAS EVAPORATING ALMOST INSTANTLY UPON CONTACT WITH OUTSIDE AIR. MR. DEDOW REPORTED HIS FINDING TO THE YARDMASTER, AND CR'S RISK MANAGEMENT DEPT. (A. RICHTER). SHIPPER/PREPARER OF THE CAR, IMTT, BAYONNE, NJ (FOR ACCOUNT OF ASHLAND CHEMICAL, COLUMBUS, OH), WAS NOTIFIED AND DISPATCHED PERSONNEL TO THE YARD. IMTT PERSONNEL NOTED THE THREADED LIQUID VALVE WAS NOT TOOL TIGHT ON THE EDUCTION PIPE. VALVE WAS REPORTEDLY TIGHTENED APPROXIMATELY 1 FULL TURN, STOPPING THE LEAK. IMTT AND FRA'S DEDOW OBSERVED THE VALVE FOR THE NEXT 30 MINUTES, AND WERE SATISFIED THE LEAK ORIGINATION HAD BEEN STOPPED. CAR OKAYED TO ORIGINAL DESTINATION.

column168: BNSF SWITCH CREW REPORTED PRODUCT ODOR EMANATING FROM CPDX 199008 WHILE IT WAS AT THE WEST END OF A BOWL TRACK IN PASCO RAILYARD. BNSF MECHANICAL/HAZMAT RESPONDER INSPECTED ALL THE VALVES AND FITTINGS ON CPDX 199008 AND ALSO USED A SOAP SOLUTION TO ASCERTAIN THE ORIGIN OF THE VAPOR RELEASE. NO PRECISE LEAK SOURCE PINPOINTED AFTER THE THOROUGH INSPECTION COMPLETED, BUT THE RESPONDER COULD STILL HEAR A BARELY AUDIBLE SOUND OF A VAPOR LEAK. IT WAS SUSPECTED THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE (SRV) WAS THE SOURCE OF THE VAPOR RELEASE, POSSIBLY FROM THE O-RING OR VALVE SEAT AREA. THE SRV WAS RATED AT 280.5 PSI AND LAST QUALIFIED BY TXIX IN 2000. CONSIGNEE RESPONDERS ALSO INSPECTED CPDX 199008 FINDING NO SPECIFIC LEAK SOURCE. CPDX 199008 WAS ISOLATED IN THE RAILYARD AND ALL PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED INTO TANKER TRUCKS BY 1700 HRS. PDT 9/22/2005 WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT. AFTER TRANSFER, CPDX 199008 WAS PRODUCT FREE AND WILL BE FORWARDED TO A DESIGNATED REPAIR FACILITY.

column168: BNSF MECHANICAL INSPECTION IN RAILYARD REVEALED TOTX 1008 LEAKING PRODUCT DOWN ITS SIDE SHELL. DETAILED INSPECTION CONCLUDED THAT THE LEAK SOURCE WAS THE 3 INCH BALL VALVE ATOP THE LIQUID EDUCTION PIPING. CONTAINMENT WAS PLACED AROUND THIS VALVE AND TOTX 1008 WAS CAREFULLY MOVED AND ISOLATED AT THE REPAIR TRACK. ALL SPILLAGE HAD EVAPORATED. SHIPPER CONTRACT RESPONDERS (RESCAR) REPLACED THIS VALVE IN KIND ON 9/25/05. CLOSER INSPECTION INDICATED THE VALVE HANDLE HAD BEEN BENT TO FIT UNDER THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER. IT IS LIKELY THAT THE VALVE HANDLE OPERATING ROD/VALVE STEM OR THE TEFLON PACKING MAY HAVE BEEN DAMAGED DURING THIS EXTERNAL HANDLE ADJUSTMENT. DAYLIGHT HEATING AND INCREASING INTERNAL PRESSURE FORCED PRODUCT OUT OF THE CLOSED VALVE AT THE HANDLE OPERATING ROD/VALVE STEM.

column168: DURING AN INITIAL CAR INSPECTION, A CAR INSPECTOR SMELLED AN ODOR AND SAW LIQUID COMING FROM A CONTAINER ON FLATCAR UPCX 930109 AT BUFFALO FRONTIER YARD. THE CAR INSPECTOR NOTIFIED THE TRAINMASTER WHO CALLED THE PCC-POLICE COMMUNICATION CENTER. A HAZMAT SENTINEL RESPONDED WITH A CDXT HAZMAT CONTRACTOR. BOTH CONTAINERS ON FLATCAR UPCX 930109 WERE PLACARDED CLASS 3 AND CLASS 8. A BUCKET WAS PLACED UNDER THE DRIPPAGE FROM CONTAINER CHES 134221. THE CAR WAS PLACED IN A SAFE AREA AND A RIGGING CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED TO LIFT THE CONTAINERS OFF UPCX 930109. THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND PRODUCT INFORMATION WAS REQUESTED. ALL PRODUCTS ARE LISTED AS HAZWASTE ON THE WAYBILL AND MOVED ON A HAZWASTE MANIFEST. CONTAINERS CHES 134221 & CLHA 136190 WERE LIFTED OFF FLATCAR UPCX 93019, AND STAGED ON POLY. (A)THE CSXT CONTRACTOR RESPONSE TEAM ENTERED CONTAINER CLHA136190, FOUND AN EMPTY STEEL DRUM OF UN1593, WASTE DICHLOROMETHANE, AT THE REAR OF THE CONTAINER. A STAINED AREA AROUND THE BOTTOM OF THE STEEL DRUM WAS NOTED. THE DRUM WAS REMOVED AND INSPECTED. TWO PUNCTURES WERE FOUND IN THE BOTTOM OF THE STEEL DRUM, APPROXIMATELY 1/2" X 3/8" WIDE. THE LEAKING DRUM WAS PLACED IN A POLY OVERPACK DRUM. THE PUNCTURES IN THE STEEL DRUM WERE CAUSED BY SCREWS IN THE FLOOR OF THE CONTAINER USED TO SECURE THE FLOOR PLATE. SEVERAL BROKEN SCREW HEADS WERE FOUND UNDER THE DRUM. THE INVESTIGATION FOUND THAT PROPER BLOCKING & BRACING PROCEDURES WERE NOT FOLLOWED.  (B) THE CSXT CONTRACTOR RESPONSE TEAM ENTERED CONTAINER CHES 134221, FOUND A PLASTIC DRUM OF UN3093, CORROSIVE LIQUID, OXIDZING, N.O.S. (HYDROFLUORIC ACID, HYDROGEN PEROXIDE) LEAKING FROM THE BUNG PLUG.  THE PRODUCT HAD SPILLED ONTO THE SIDE OF THE DRUM IMPACTING A STEEL DRUM NEXT TO IT.  THE PLASTIC DRUM OF HAZ-WASTE WAS REMOVED AND PLACED IN A PLOY OVERPACK DRUM FOR CONTAINMENT.  THE INVESTIGATION FOUND THAT PROPER BLOCKING & BRACING PROCEDURES WERE NOT FOLLOWED.  (C) THE CSXT CONTRACTOR RESPONSE TEAM ENTERED CONTAINER CHES 134221, FOUND A STEEL DRUM OF UN1993, WASTE FLAMMABLE LIQUID, N.O.S. (ACETONE/METHANOL) LEAKING DOWN THE SIDE OF THE DRUM IMPACTING THE STEEL DRUM, CAUSING THE SHIME TO CORRODE AND LEAK.  THE LEAKING DRUM WAS REMOVED AND PACKED AND PLACED INTO A POLY OVERPACK DRUM.  THE INVESTIGATION FOUND THAT PROPER BLOCKING & BRACING PROCEDURES WERE NOT FOLLOWED.
column169: THE SHIPPER MUST ADHERE TO AAR APPROVED LOADING GUIDELINES FOR HAZWASTE INTO CONTAINERS. THE SHIPPER SHOULD DEVELOP A PROCESS TO INSPECT ALL LADING FOR LEAKS BEFORE AND AFTER LOADING AND PROPERLY INSPECT THE SHIPPING CONTAINER BEFORE LOADING DRUMS.

column168: AS EMPLOYEE WAS UNLOADING PALLET OF HAZMAT FROM TRAILER, A PIECE OF METAL (THE SHIPMENT LOADED IN FRONT OF HAZMAT) SHIFTED DUE TO NOT BEING SECURED IN TRAILER. IT FELL AGAINST THE HAZMAT PALLET, PUNCTURING 1 BOX. IT CAUSED A 2 INCH TEAR IN ONE 2 1/2 GALLON PAIL. THE PAIL WAS IMMEDIATELY TURNED ON ITS SIDE TO PREVENT FURTHER LEAKING. WOOD SHAVINGS WERE IMMEDIATELY USED TO ABSORB SPILL WHICH WAS LIMITED TO APPX. 4 FOOT X 4 FOOT SPILL IN THE TRAILER. MATERIAL WAS ABSORBED AND EVAPORATED. SHIPMENT NOW IN GARDENA OSD DEPT.
column169: SPILL REPORT WAS COMPLETED AND FORWARDED TO ORIGIN SERVICE CENTER WITH EMPLOYEE NAME OF THOSE INVOLVED. EMPLOYEE AT GARDENA WAS TRAINED ON HOW THIS MAY HAVE BEEN PREVENTED, FOLLOW-UP WITH AM DOCK MEETING TO TRAIN SHIFT WILL FOLLOW.

column168: THE SHRINK WRAPPED SHIPMENT WAS FOUND LEAKING OUT OF THE BOTTOM BOX. UPON SEPARATING THE BOX FROM THE SHIPMENT, I NOTICED THE BOX DENTED IN ONE CORNER. AFTER, OPENING THE BOX I FOUND 1 OF THE 2 CANS IN THE BOX DENTED NEAR THE BOTTOM AND THE LID WAS BENT OPEN. THE CAN ONLY LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 2 OZ. THE SMALL PUDDLE WAS CLEANED UP W/ ABSORBENT AND PLACED INTO OSD.
column169: EXTRA CARE AND RESPECT SHOULD BE TAKEN WHEN HANDLING ON WORKING AROUND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. IN THIS CASE, ADEQUATE DUNNAGE SHOULD BE PLACED ON OR AROUND THE HM SHIPMENT TO PREVENT DAMAGE THAT COULD LEAD TO A SPILL.

column168: CARTONS WERE LOADED ONTO PALLETS BY SHIPPER. NO CARDBOARD OR OTHER DUNNAGE/BUFFER WAS PLACED BETWEEN THE CARTONS AND THE PALLET. AS DOCKWORKER WAS UNLOADING SHIPMENT FROM TRAILER, A NAIL FROM THE PALLET WAS PUSHED UPWARD FROM THE PALLET INTO THE CARTON, PUNCTURING ONE CARTON. (THE BLADE OF THE FORKLIFT LIFTING UP ON THE PALLET CAUSED THE NAIL TO PUNCTURE CTN.) THE DURATION OF THE LEAK WAS APPX. 30-45 SECONDS. THE CARTON WAS REMOVED FROM THE PALLET, AND TURNED ON ITS SIDE TO PREVENT FURTHER LEAKING. ABSORBENT WAS USED TO CONTAIN AND SOAK UP MATERIAL. INNER PACKAGING WAS DAMAGED. HOLE WAS
column169: UNABLE TO SUGGEST CHANGES TO SHIPPER, OTHER THAN TO USE CARDBOARD BETWEEN CTNS AND PALLET. INSTRUCTIONAL MEETINGS TO FEDEX DOCK EMPLOYEES WERE PERFORMED TO AID IN PREVENTING FUTURE OCCURRENCES.

column168: DRIVER WAS UNLOADING AND WAS NOT AWARE THAT CONSIGNEES STORAGE TANKS WERE CLOSED. THE ONLY TANK OPEN WAS THEIR 1500 OVERFILL TANK. THIS TANK FILLED, SWELLED AND RIPPED OPEN SPILLING APPROX 2100 GALLONS INSIDE THE TANK FARM BUILDING. IN-PLANT RESPONSE TEAM AND HAZMAT RESPONSE PICKED UP SPILL INTO BARRELS FOR DISPOSAL.
THE PAIL IN QUESTION APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN PUNCTURED DURING THE LOADING PROCESS BY A FORKLIFT BLADE.
column169: REPORT SENT TO FACILITY WHERE INCIDENT CAUSED IDENTIFYING THE CIRCUMSTANCES AND THE CORRECTIVE ACTION NECESSARY. MEETING ALSO TO BE HELD WITH ENTIRE SHIFT TO REINFORCE THE PROPER HANDLING PROCEDURES TO PREVENT THIS FROM OCCURRING.
column172: Pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column168: UPON ARRIVAL AT ORD PALLET PMC24041MU WAS FOUND TO BE LEANING IN THE AIRCRAFT TO THE EXTENT THAT THE PALLED HAD TO BE OPENED AND SOME DRUMS WERE REMOVED BY THE RAMP HANDLING COMPANY GLOBE GROUND. THE PALLET WAS THEN REMOVED FROM THE AIRCRAFT AND PUT ON A TRANSPORTING DOLLIE. SWISSPORT AGENT TIM SOLAK THEN PROCEEDED TO USE A FORKLIFT (#6) TO REMOVE THE PALLET FROM THE DOLLIE AND PLACE IT ON THE GROUND. MR. SOLAK STATED THE PALLET JUST KEPT TIPPING OVER UNTIL HE NOTICED THE LIQUID COMING OUT THE SIDE OF THE BARRELS. AT THIS POINT MANAGEMENTWAS NOTIFIED.     MR. SEJFUDIN SUBASIC WAS WORKING AROUND 300 YARDS AWAY BUT COMPLAINED OF FEELING ILL WAS SENT TO THE CLINIC AS PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE.
column169: HAVE ADVISED ALL STAFF THAT PALLETS ARE TO BE PULLED INSIDE THE FACILITY FOR BREAKDOWN, AND THAT ANY SHIFING PALLETS ARE TO BE MOVED ONLY WITH SUPERVISOR PRESENT IN ORDER TO PREVENT ANY FURTHER DAMAGE OR INJURY. IF ALL BARRELS WERE REMOVED IMMEDIATELY THIS INCIDENT COULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED.

column168: PAIL WAS CRUSHED WHILE STAGED ON WHI DOCK. IT WAS PUSHED AGAINST A PALLET.
column169: TO PREVENT REOCCURENCE, WE WILL HOLD A DOCK MEETING REGARDING THE NEED TO PREVENT THIS FROM REOCCURENCE. WHILE YOU ARE OPERATING A FORKLIFT YOU NEED TO STAY FOCUSED, LOOK AHEAD OF WHAT IS IN FRONT AND WATCH WHERE YOU STAGE YOUR FREIGHT.

column168: DOCK MAN DID NOT BLOCK FREIGHT IN AND WHEN TRAILER WAS MOVED TO YARD BOX FELL AND ONE BOTTLE FELL OUT AND HIT ON CUP. CUP FAILED.
column169: DOCK MAN AND YARD MAN WILL CHECK BLOCKING BEFORE TRAILER IS MOVED.

column168: THIS INCIDENT TOOK PLACE DURING LOAD OUT TIME. THE EMPLOYEE WAS GOING TO REWORK THE NOSE OF A TRAILER GOING TO WHITTIER, HE ENTERED THE TRAILERS AT A NORMAL RATE OF SPEED. HE PICKED UP THE PALLET OF DRUMS BUT HAD A PROBLEM WITH ROPES AROUND IT. HE THEN EXITED THE FORKLIFT, LEAVING HIS FORKS UP, AND DIDNT USE THE HAND BRAKE. THE FORKLIFT ROLLED FORWARD, PUNCTURING ONE DRUM. THIS LEFT ONE FORKHOLE IN THE DRUM. THE PUNCTURE WAS ABOUT 6 INCHES WIDE. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP VERY QUICK.
column169: I WENT OVER THE RULES OF SAFETY ON THE FORKLIFT WITH THE INDIVIDUAL, AS WELL AS PROPER UNLOADING AND LOADING TECHNIQUES WHCIH SHOULD ALWAYS BE FOLLOWED. DISCIPLINARY ACTION WAS TAKEN, THE EMPLOYEE WAS GIVEN A WRITTEN WARNING AND WAS ALSO SUSPENDED FROM THE FORKLIFT FOR 30 DAYS.

column168: POST PICK UP OF THIS FREIGHT SHIPMENT AT APPROCIMATELY 1630 OUR DRIVER NOTICED FLUID IN HIS TRAILER. HE NOTIFIED DISPATCH WHO ADVISED HIM TO RETURN TO THE SHIPPER. UPON RETURNING TO THE SHIPPER THEY CONTAINED THE MATERIAL W/ ABSORBENT AND REMOVED THE CONTAINERS FROM OUR TRAILER.   UPON INSPECTION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE OF THE CONTAINERS HAD TWO AREAS WHERE IT WAS COMPROMISED ON ONE SIDE OF THE CONTAINER WAS A SLIT, "2-3" LONG THROUGH WHICH FLUID SEEPED ON THE OPPOSITE SIDE OF THE CONTAINER WAS DISCOVERED ANOTHER SLIT, ABOUT "3-4" LONG THAT HAD OPENED BY APPROXIMATELY "4" OR BETTER. BOTH SLITS WERE ABOVE THE MID LINE, NEARER TO THE TOP OF THE CONTAINER.
column169: WE'VE ADVISED THE SHIPPER THAT THEY TENDERED US A FAULTY OR DEFECTIVE CONTAINER. THEY ARE AWARE OF THE PROBLEM AND HAVE INDICATED THAT THEY WILL CHECK THEIR CONTAINERS AND INVESTIGATE THE MATTER.

column168: ON SEPT 22, 2005 APX. 1145 AM DAVID HOLLEY, A PETROLEUM TRANSPORT COMPANY DRIVER. column168: CN MECHANICAL EMPLOYEE NOTED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE TANK SHELL OF TANK CAR UTLX 12134 WHILE INSPECTING RAIL CARS IN THE CHAMPAIGN YARD, URBANA, IL.  ALL APPROPRIATE DEPARTMENTS NOTIFIED.  SHIPPER'S RESPONSE CONTRACTOR AND CN'S HAZMAT TEAM RESPONDED.  TANK CAR WAS ISOLATED AND A 300 GALLON CONTAINER WAS PLACED UNDER THE TANK CAR TO CAPTURE LEAKING PRODUCT.  PRODUCT WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING FROM A 1.5" HOLE ON THE LEFT CENTER SIDE, APPROXIMATELY 30" FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK SHELL.  PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED INTO TANK CAR GATX 61250.  UTLX 12134 WAS PURGED AND CLEANED OF ALL RESIDUE PRODUCT FOR MOVEMENT TO A REPAIR FACILITY BY THE SHIPPER.
column169: NO ADDITIONAL COMMENTS.

column168: A PALLET OF PAILS WAS DOCKED DURING UNLOAD OF SHIPMENT.  THE FREIGHT HANDLER STARTED THE PALLET WAS IN GOOD CONDITION.  A FEW MINUTES LATER THE PALLET HAD BEEN STRUCK BY A FORKLIFT, THE CORNER OF THE WOOD PALLET WAS BROKEN AND THE PAILS WERE PUSHED TOGETHER.  ONE OF THE PAILS WAS CRUSHED TO THE POINT IT OPENED THE LID.  TWO GALLONS OF PRODUCT LEAKED OUT OF THE FIVE GALLON PAIL.  THE PRODUCT SPILLED ONTO THE DOCK.  THE CRUSHED PAIL WAS REMOVED FROM THE SHIPMENT AND PLACED IN OS&D.  THE REST OF THE SHIPMENT WAS CLEANED, RECOUPED, AND SENT OUT FOR DELIVERY.
column169: BRIEFED ALL FORKLIFT OPERATORS TO BE MORE AWARE OF THEIR SURROUNDINGS WHEN DRIVING THE FORKLIFT.

column168: DRIVER FINISHED UNLOADING WENT TO UNHOOK HOSES.  HOSES WERE NOT COMPLETELY EMPTY.  DRIVER WAS UNAWARE THAT THE HOSES WEREN'T COMPLETELY EMPTY.  SPILL OCCURRED FROM PRODUCT LEFT IN HOSES.  DRIVER SECURED AND CAPPED HOSES VENTURE PLANT PERSONNEL CLEANED UP SPILL.  DRIVER REPORTED SPILL TO TERMINAL.
column169: ADDITIONAL TRAINING OF DRIVER MIGHT HAVE PREVENTED SPILL.

column168: AN OPERATOR WAS MOVING LOADED STYRENE TANK CARS.  HE SMELLED STYRENE AND UPON LOOKING FOR ODOR FOUND PSPX 23561 LOADED STYRENE TANK CAR BELLY VALVE HAD A DRIP OF STYRENE COMING FROM AT.  THE OPERATOR PUT A BUCKET UNDER THE VALVE TO CAPTURE MATERIAL THE TANK CAR WAS BROUGHT BACK TO THE LOADING AREA AND AN ATTEMPT WAS MADE TO STOP THE LEAK.  THE LEAK WOULDN'T STOP.  THE PSPX 23561 TANK CAR WAS OFF LOADED TO GATX 54645.  PSPX-23561 WAS BAD ORDERED AND WILL HAVE THE BELLY VALVE REPAIRED.  THE TANK CAR WILL THEN BE PRESSURED AND TESTED AND OKAYED FOR SERVICE BEFORE LOADING AGAIN.
column169: PSPX-23561 WILL HAVE BELLY VALVE REPAIRED OR REPLACED.  IT WILL BE INSPECTED AND PRESSURED TESTED, BEFORE BEING USED AGAIN FOR SERVICE.

DRIVER WAS GOING TO FAST FOR A  15 MPH TURN.  THE TRUCK AND TRAILER THEN ROLLED OVER AND TANK STARTED LEAKING OUT APPROX 6700 GALLONS OF ETHANOL.  ACCIDENT HAPPENED AT 11:55 AM, INTER-STATE OIL COMPANYS EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM (NRC) WAS ON SITE WITHIN 1 HOUR.  LOCAL AUTHORITIES FINALLY ALLOWED NRC TO RESPOND AT 9:00PM.  THIS IS WHY 6700 GALLONS WAS LOST.

column168: (A)A BNSF TRAIN ENROUTE TO EAGLE PASS, TX DERAILED 8 RAILCARS, INCLUDING FIVE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL LADENED TANK CARS, ON UPRR MAIN TRACK. THE UPRR CONTRIBUTED THE CAUSE OF THIS DERAILMENT TO A BROKEN RAIL. ADMX 30167 DERAILED UPRIGHT BUT LEANING AND DRIPPED PRODUCT FROM THE BOLTED FLANGE PLATE THAT THE LIQUID VALVE FLANGE WAS BOLTED UPON. CONTRACT RESPONDERS COULD NOT TIGHTEN THE BOLTS ON THIS FLANGE PLATE WITHOUT REMOVING THE UPPER FLANGE AND VALVE ASSEMBLY. CONTRACTORS APPLIED PLUG-N-DIKE PUTTY TO THE OUTER FLANGE CIRCUMFERENCE TO STOP THE PRODUCT DRIPS. ADMX 30167 WAS UPRGITHED TO ASSURE NO FURTHER PRODUCT ESCAPING FROM THE PUTTY SEALED FLANGE. CONTRACTORS INSPECTED THE GROUND SOIL UNDER ADMX 30167 FINDING LITTLE EVIDENCE OF PRODUCT IMPACT. HIGH AMBIENT TEMPERATURES EVAPORATED PRODUCT SPILLAGE. DAMAGES TO ADMX 30167 NECESSITATED SCHEDULING PRODUCT TRANSFTER TO ANOTHER SUITABLE TANK CAR.      (B)A BNSF TRAIN ENROUTE TO EAGLE PASS, TX DERAILED 8 RAILCARS, INCLUDING FIVE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL LADENED TANK CARS, ON UPRR MAIN TRACK.  THE UPRR CONTRIBUTED THE CAUSE OF THIS DERAILMENT TO A BROKEN RAIL.  WACX 151069 DERAILED ON ITS SIDE AND DRIPPED PRODUCT FROM RHE LIQUID EDUCTION PIPE ASSEMBLY FLANGE AREA.  CONTRACT RESPONDERS TIGHTENED FOUR LOOSE FLANGE BOLTS ON THE LIQUID LINE ENDING FURTHER PRODUCT RELEASE.  CONTRACTORS APPLIED NEUTRALIZER TO THE SPILLAGE THAT HAS ACCUMULATED ON THE GROUND UNDER THE LEAK AREA.  INPACTED SOIL WAS EXCAVATED AND TAKEN TO AN APPROPRIATE DISPOSAL FACLILITY.  DAMAGES TO WACX 151069 NECESSITATED SCHEDULING PRODUCT TRANSFER TO ANOTHER SUITABLE TANK CAR.

column14: MCCARRAN RD E/B I-80 OFF RAMP
column168: TRUCK & SEMI TRAILER WAS E/B ON THE MCCARRAN EXIT RAMP.  IN SPARKS, NV.  DRIVER HAD A GREEN LIGHT FOR A LEFT TURN AT BOTTOM OF RAMP.  DRIVER WAS TRAVELING TO FAST FOR LEFT (SHARP) TURN WITH FULL LOAD OF DYED KERO.  TRAILER OVERTURNED ONTO ITS RIGHT SIDE ON MCCARRAN RD UNDER I-80.  WHEN TRAILER OVERTURNED ONTO ITS RIGHT SIDE ON MCCARRAN RD UNDER I-80.  WHEN TRAILER OVERTURNED IT ALSO CAUSED TRUCK TRACTOR TO OVERTURN ONTO ITS RIGHT SIDE.  NO INJURIES, NO OTHER PARTIES INVOLVED.  FRONT COMPARTMENT ON TRAILER FRACTURED AT DOME LID WHEN DOME LID STRUCK A CONCRETE PILLAR.  THIS CAUSED FUEL TO SPILL OUT RAPIDLY OUT OF FRONT COMPARTMENT.  THE CENTER 2 COMPARTMENTS UPON IMPACT WITH ROADWAY.  THIS WAS A SLOW LEAK.  AN ENVIRONMENTAL CLEAN UP COMPANY (H20 ENVIRONMENTAL) WHICH IS LOCATED IN SPARKS, NV.  RESPONDED IMMEDIATELY TO THE SCENE AND QUICKLY CONTAINED SPILLING FUEL OVER THE NEXT SEVERAL DAYS THIS COMPANY COMPLETELY CLEANED UP ALL SPILLED FUEL & REMOVED CONTAMINATED SOIL.  NEVADA DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION SUPERVISED THE CLEAN UP OPERATION.  AS OF THIS DATE (10-13-05) CLEAN UP IS COMPLETED WITH THE APPROVAL OF THE APPROPRIATE AGENCIES.
column169: CONTINUE DRIVER TRAINING & IMPORTANCE OF SAFETY RELATED TO DRIVERS SAFETY WHILE DRIVING WITH LIQUID HAZ-MAT.  DRIVER WILL BE COUNSELED ON SAFE DRIVER PRACTICES AND REQUIRED TO VIEW A TRAINING TAPE ON SAFE DRIVING PRACTICES WITH LIQUID LOADS.  HE WILL ALSO BE CLOSELY MONITORED.

column168: ON SEPTEMBER 26, 2005 AT APPROXIMATELY 12:30 PM, AN EXXONMOBIL TRACTOR AND TRAILER WAS TRAVELING NORTH ON RT. 24 IN TAUNTON, MA.  THE TRUCK WAS IN THE RIGHT LANE AND WAS PASSING A CONTRACTOR PERFORMING GUARD RAIL WORK IN THE BREAKDOWN LANE.  THE EXXONMOBIL TRUCK AND TRAILER WAS ABLE TO PASS THE WORK CREW HALF WAY WHEN ALLEGEDLY A LARGE SWIVEL AND COUNTER VALANCE SWING INTO THE RIGHT LANE, STRIKING THE MIDDLE OF THE TRAILER APPROX. 6 FEET HIGH.  IT STRUCK THE TRAILER TWO MORE TIMES BEFORE IT TORE A HOLE IN THE VERY REAR OF THE TRAILER SPILLING PRODUCT ONTO THE ROAD.  INVESTIGATE CONTINUES.  POLICE REPORT IS STILL PENDING.
column169: REVIEWED THE INCIDENT WITH ALL DRIVERS AT 9/27/2005 SAFETY MEETING.

column168: FILE-5-317 DOT SHIPPER-CHEVRON USA AWB#-MCN 8754704895 ATL  ON 09/23/2005 AT 0307, AN ODOROUS SHIPMENT WAS REPORTED IN THE HAZ SORT BUILDING LOCATED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177.  SPILL TECHNICIANS RICKEY DAVIS JR AND MICHELLE EICHER DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL, THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX EMITTING AN ODOR.  THEY REMOVED THE PACKAGE FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION.  UPON THIS INVESTIGATION, THEY FOUND THIS PACKAGE TO CONTAIN 4 X 16 OUNCE GLASS BOTTLES OF GAS OIL AND DIESEL FUEL.  DUE TO A LOOSE CLOSURE, 32 OUNCES OF THE PRODUCT WAS LOST.  THIS SHIPMENT ARRIVED INTO WILMINGTON VIA FLIGHT #381, N796AX.  THIS SHIPMENT DID HAVE MARKINGS/LABELS AND A SHIPPERS DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO AND ACCOMPANYING IT TO INDICATE THAT THIS WAS A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  CLEAR OF SCENE: 0335. column168: THE TRANSPORT VEHICLE LEFT THE ROADWAY (NC HIGHWAY 96) TO THE RIGHT, OVERTURNED AND COLLIDED WITH A FIRE HYDRANT.  THE FIRE HYDRANT PUNCTURED THE TANKER BODY, RESULTING IN THE RELEASE OF PRODUCT.  THE DIESEL FUEL IMPACTED THE GROUND SURFACE IMMEDIATELY AROUND AND DOWNGRADIENT OF THE FUEL RESTING POSITION OF THE TANKER.  EMERGENCY RESPONSE ACTIVITIES INCLUDED THE CONSTRUCTION OF SOIL BAUMS AND OFF-LOADING OF PRODUCT REMAINING IN THE UNDAMAGED TANKER COMPARTMENTS.  ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE ACTIVITIES INCLUDED THE EVACUATION OF APPROXIMATELY 3500 TONS OF PETROLEUM IMPACTED SOIL.  THE IMPACTED SOIL WAS TRANSPORTED OFF-SITE FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL, AND THE EXCAVATION WAS BACKFILLED WITH CLEAN SOIL.

column168: MECHANICAL PERSONNEL AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN ROCHESTER, NY, REPORTED THAT TANK CAR ACFX 79911, LEAD DIESEL FUEL, WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. A BUCKET WAS PLACED UNDER THE VALVE TO CONTAIN THE LEAK. THE SHIPPER, UNITED REFINING, WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC. CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO REPAIR THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK. UNITED REFINING ALSO RESPONDED A TEAM. THE RESPONDERS FOUND THAT THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP. THE TOP OPERATING ROD FOR THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS FOUND TO BE LOOSE ALLOWING THE OUTLET VALVE TO BE OPEN SLIGHTLY. THEY CLOSED THE VALVE AND THE LEAK STOPPED. THE BOTTOM OUTLET WAS DRAINED AND THE OUTLET CAP WAS REMOVED. THEY INSTALLED A NEW CAP GASKET AND RE-ATTACHED THE CAP WRENCH TIGHT. THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.  CAUSE CODE: 533  NARRI: 5(5+1+0) X (2+0) = 60

ON 09/13/2005 15:24 CSX TRANSPORTATION RECEIVED A CALL FROM FRA INSPECTOR MATSINGER REPORTING TANK CAR GPPX 9414 LOCATED AT CSXT HAGERSTOWN YARD HAD WHAT APPEARED TO BE A SPLASH LEAK ON THE TOP OF THE CAR. INSPECTOR MATSINGER ADVISED ALL THE MANWAY BOLTS APPEARED TO BE TOOL TIGHT. CSX TRANSPORTATION HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SYSTEMS MADE SHIPPER NOTIFICATION VIA CHEMTREC. A RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS DISPATCHED TO INSPECT THE CAR AND MAKE REPAIRS. THE CONTRACTOR FOUND THE MANWAY GASKET WAS SLIGHTLY SMALLER, NOT WIDE ENOUGH TO FORM A SEAL. A BOOT TYPE GASKET WAS PLACED ON THE NOZZLE AND ALL BOLTS WERE RETIGHTENED. A GOOD SEAL WAS ESTABLISHED. TANK CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION WITH NO FURTHER DEFECTS. SHIPPER WAS ADVISED OF DEFECT WITH MANWAY GASKET.
column169: SHIPPER SHOULD DEVELOP A PROCESS TO INSPECT ALL MANWAY GASKETS FOR POSITIVE SEAL CONDITION BEFORE OFFERING RAIL CARS FOR TRANSPORTATION.

THE TRUCK AND/OR A PIECE OF THE RIVETED STEEL GUARDRAIL FROM THE EXIT RAMP HIT TANK CARS PLMX 35151 AND PLMX 35190, BOTH CONTAINING THE RESIDUE OF ISOBUTANE (PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEIFED, 2.1, UN 1075) WHICH WERE IN CSXT TRAIN Q41816. TANK CARS NOTED WERE PLACED 40TH AND 41ST RESPECTIVELY, IN TOTAL TRAIN LENGTH OF 57 CARS. NO RAILCARS WERE DERAILED IN THE INCIDENT. PLMX 35190 WAS NOTED TO BE OFF CENTER FROM THE TRUCK IMPACT, AND FORCE OF THE TRUCK'S LOAD AGAINST THE CAR. CAR CONDITION CORRECTED AT TIME OF CLEARING OF INCIDENT AREA WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT. TRACK ALSO NOTED TO HAVE BEEN MOVED APPROXIMATELY 4" OUT OF GAUGE (CORRECTED PRIOER TO CLEARANCE OF INCIDENT).    IMPACT OF GUARDRAIL APPEARED TO HAVE DAMAGED MECHANICAL AND SAFETY APPLIANCES OF PLMX 35151, AT THE BR CORNER. NEITHER CAR WAS DERAILED. THIS TANK CAR REPORTED TO BE SHOPPED AT CSXT'S S. KEARNY RAIL YARD FOR INSPECTION AND REPAIR.   TRASH TRUCK ASSISTANT PRONOUNCED DEAD AT SCENE. TRUCK DRIVER TAKEN TO LOCAL HOSPITAL WHERE IT WAS REPORTED THE HE EVENTUALLY SUCCUMBED TO HIS INJURIES. THE DRUMS WERE PATCHED AND PLACED INTO SALVAGE DRUMS FOR SECUREMENT. LESS THAN A GALLON OF PRODUCT HAD ESCAPED AND POOLED ON THE TOPS OF THE DRUMS. THE CONTAINER WAS CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE, AND THE DRUMS PLACED BACK ONTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER. column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 4:40 AM ON SEPTEMBER 29, 2005 A VAN TRAILER OPERATED BY CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC (CHESI) EXPERIENCED A MINOR RELEASE OF HAZARDOUS WASTE FROM A NON-BULK PACKAGE. AT THE TIME OF THE RELEASE THE VEHICLE WAS PARKED ON THE SIDE OF THE ROAD AT THE INTERSECTION OF RT. 279 SOUTH AND RT. 79 NEAR PITTSBURGH, PENNSYLVANIA. DURING A REGULAR LOAD SECUREMENT CHECK THE DRIVER NOTICED A SMALL LEAK COMING OUT OF THE BACK OF THE TRAILER. HE IMMEDIATELY SECURED THE AREA TO PREVENT UNAUTHORIZED ACCESS. HE THEN RETRIEVED THE SHIPPING PAPERS AND NOTIFIED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CENTER OF THE INCIDENT. AN IN-HOUSE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREW WAS DISPATCHED TO IDENTIFY THE SOURCE OF THE RELEASE AND TO TAKE ALL NECESSARY CORRECTIVE ACTIONS. PENNSYLVANIA STATE POLICE WERE ALSO NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. UPON REVIEW OF THE PAPERWORK, THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREW DONNED APPROPRIATE PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND ENTERED THE TRAILER. AN INSPECTION OF THE NON BULK PACKAGES IN THE TRAILER IDENTIFIED THAT A SINGLE 55-GALLON UN 1A2 CONTAINER OF CLASS 3 LIQUID EXPERIENCED A MATERIAL FAILURE NEAR THE BOTTOM OF THE CONTAINER. THE RESPONSE CREW IMMEDIATELY USED A CHEMICALLY COMPATIBLE ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO CONTAIN APPROXIMATELY 25 GALLONS OF LIQUID THAT WAS RELEASED TO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER AS WELL AS APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF MATERIAL THAT ACTUALLY DRIPPED FROM THE BACK OF THE VAN TRAILER ONTO THE ASPHALT. THE LEAKING DRUM WAS PLACED IN A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM AND ALL OF THE ABSORBENT WAS COLLECTED AND PLACED INTO APPROPRIATE CONTAINER FOR DISPOSAL AT AN APPROVED HAZARDOUS WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY. PENNSYLVANIA STATE POLICE WERE SATISFIED WITH THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE AND THE CLEAN UP CONDUCTED BY CHESI AND NO CITATIONS OR REPORTS WERE ISSUED AT THAT TIME.

IN ADDITION WE ARE REVIEWING COMPANY GUIDANCE ON LOAD SECUREMENT TO ENSURE CONTINUED COMPLIANCE WITH DOT AND SAFE TRANSPORTATION OF DANGEROUS GOODS.

column169: On The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR), shippers are immediately notified of all HAZMAT releases. For non-accident releases (a.k.a. package or closure defects), where possible, shippers are requested to respond, repair and remediate. By immediately involving the shipper, in-depth knowledge of the release cause is gained by the same organization that can implement process changes to prevent recurrence. After each release incident, KCSR provides outreach to the shipper to help investigate root-cause factors for correction. For non-accident related releases, the shipper should be contacted directly for details associated with actions taken to prevent recurrence.

column168: An electric scooter was loaded into cargo bins 1 and 2 of TransMeridian(TMA)Flight 212, an MD-80/83 aircraft, Tail #N960PG.  Loading was performed by agents of SwissPort, who are under contract with the Sanford airport authority to perform loading services for TMA. The scooter was loaded wihout disconnecting the battery.  The aircraft then flew from Sanford Field, Orlando Florida to Toledo, Ohio.  When the cargo bins were opened to download the aircraft in Toledo, the scooter was noted to be on its side with battery acid spilled on both the scooter and on the cargo floor.  A ramp agent  employed by American Eagle at Toledo came in contact with the battery acid during the unloading process and suffered a minor burn to one hand for which he received first aid.  TMA Maintenance employees cleaned the cargo bin per FAA approved procedures.  No damage to the aircraft was noted.  The customer's scooter was also cleaned and returned to him.  Apparently the customer spoke to TMA agent Tiffany Schaffer in Orlando and told her that the battery was of the gel cell type.  In fact, the battery was found to be a lawn and garden battery for a lawnmower and was not a Non-Spillable type.  The Staff Vice President of Safety at TMA, along with the Vice President of Customer Service and the TMA Station Manager at Sanford were immediately notified and held a conference with senior members at Swissport the following day.  Swissport has agreed to retrain all their employees on the proper way to secure wheelchair and/or scooter batteries.
column169: See previous page.  The company providing loading services has agreed to retrain all employees at that location.

column168: Today at approximately 1145, during security screening, Jon Gower(warehouse supervisor) discovered an undeclared DG under AWB # 125-7882 5585, 29pcs, 1,625Kg. from UPS/Menlo. The particular HAWB # is 5435164680, 10 pcs, 53Kg. Upon finding the first DG( UN 3316 First Aid Kit), Kyle Stuart, Operations Mgr. assisted Jon Gower in screening the rest of the HAWB. At this time another undeclared DG was discovered which had no proper shipping name attached. However, there were three DG labels affixed to the pipe which was inside an unmarked box and these labels were; 1) Inhilation hazard label, 2) Oxidizer label and 3) a Corrosive label.    Jon Gower brought the situation to my attention at which time the following people/organizations were contacted in the order given;   Jeff Lyter, Director of Safety and Security, Air General  Woody Ward,Gateway Manager, UPS/Menlo  Barbara Wilson, ACSM, British Airways  Paul Klimas, FAA, Regional Office  Chris Vander Hoek, TSA, Aviation Security Inspector  Jim McCaffrey, VP Security, British Airways    After confering with Jim McCaffrey, the TSA and FAA, the 10 pcs belonging to the suspect HAWB were placed on hold and segregated in the warehouse. UPS wished to send the remaining 19pcs on todays flight which did occur but not before each piece was screened, including all crates and banded freight(UPS came to our warehouse and re-banded everything after inspection).    The TSA and FAA are scheduled to arrive at our facility at 9:00 AM on Sep. 16  to inspect the freight on hold. An eBasis report has been filed and the reference number is 257677. Once the TSA and FAA have finished with the freight and thier report I will forward any relevant information. It should be noted that UPS/Menlo was very helpful and cooperative during the entire process

column168: On 9-16-05 at approximately 1500 hours Apria employee Robert McLeod was driving Apria truck #21230P, a box truck containing a non-specification carho tank, when he experienced an unintended release of Oxygen, refrigerated liquid.    McLeod had just completed a delivery ( no oxygen, refrigerated liquid involved) to a patient in Poulsbo, WA and was enroute to his next scheduled delivery. As he was entering the on ramp from 308 onto Hwy 3 he looked in mirror and observed a liquid running out of the side door (curb side) of the cargo area. He pulled onto the shoulder, activated the vehicles emergency flashers, shut down the engine and proceeded to the cargo door. Upon opening the door he found that the piping was broken between the fill valve and the tank body. Due to the location of the break there was no way to shut off the leak.    McLeod proceeded to the bottom of the ramp so that he could divert traffic away from the vehicle and contacted his supervisor on his cell phone. He notified his supervisor of the circumstances and asked him to notify the local fire department and the WA State Patrol.    Andy Williams, Bremerton Branch Manager, immediately made the emergency notifications to local authorities as well as corporate notifications.    Upon arrivial at the scene fire department personnel inspected the vehicle. They determined that the cargo tank was no longer leaking and that the oxygen, refrigerated liquid that had leaked onto the dirt shoulder had vaporized and disapated. A short time later they stated that the scene was secure and had McLeod remove the vehicle from the scene.    Upon returning to the office the tank was inspected. It was discovered that a clamp securing the piping to a support had worked loose. Apparently, vibration had caused the piping to fracture, resulting in the release.    There were no injuries or collateral damage as a result of this incident.
column169: As a result of this incident all drivers at the Bremerton, WA branch received retraining on the daily inspection procedures for the truck mounted cryogenic cargo tanks. McLeod received a corrective action.    The retraining is being followed up with an article addressing the inspection requirements in the next issue of the corporate Transportation Safety Newletter.    The incident was also discussed with our contracted repair and refurbishment company. It will be policy that any vessel found to have questionable supporting of the piping by the manufacture will have additional supports installed so that there will be sufficient support should a clamp be loosened in the future.

Un-declared dangerous goods were discovered during security screening.  During security screening, warehouse supv discovered an undeclared DG under awb 125-78825585, 29pcs, 1,625 kgs. from Air Freight Forwarder UPS/Menlo. The particular HAWB # 5435164680, 10 pcs, 53 kgs. Upon finding the first DG (UN3316 First Aid Kit), Ops Mgr assisted in screening the rest of the HAWB. Another undeclared DG was discovered which had no proper shipping name attached. There were three DG labels affixed to the pipe which was inside an unmarked box and these lables were, 1) inhilation hazard label, 2) oxidizer label and 3) Corrosive label.  The FAA was contacted. They came in and took information . The shipment was not loaded but returned to UPS/Menlo for proper documentation and packaging.
column169: The FAA has contacted the shipper to advise them of their failure to follow proper shipping directives. Air General/British Airways has completed the required screening to prevent transportation of undeclared goods. There is no future action due on our part.

column62: Conveyer or Material Handling Equipment Mishap
column168: ON SAT NIGHT ON 0425 IN THE MORNING I WAS ADVISED BY MR. PETE SERANO THE MOD FOR WFS THAT THERE WAS AN INCIDENT ON THE RAMP INVOLVING A PALLET THAT CONTAINED DANGEROUS GOODS ON IT.  MR. SERANO HAD TOLD ME THAT THE PALLET HAD FALLEN FROM THE TOP OF THE MAIN DECK LOADER ALL THE WAY DOWN TO THE BOTTOM OF THE LOADER APPROX 15 FT.  I PULLED ALL THE PAPERWORK TO FOUND OUT WHAT DANGEROUS GOODS WERE LOADED ON IT.  DUE TO THE SIGNIFICANT AMOUNT OF DG'S I CALLED THE PA POLICE IMMEDIATELY AND ADV THEM OF THE HAZ MAT SPILL THIS WAS 0430 L.  I THEN MADE COPIES OF ALL THE PAPERWORK FOR THE HAZMAT RESPONSE TEAM.  AND AT 0435 L I CALLED MR. JOE CARNI AT HOME TO ADVISE HIM OF THE SITUATION.  AT 0437 L I MET WITH THE RESPONSE TEAM AND WAS TOLD TO SUSPEND ALL OPERATIONS.  ALL CARGO LOADING STOPPED AS WELL AS FUELING.  I KEPT COORDINATING WITH THE RESPONSE TEAM AND AT 0600 L WE WERE GIVEN THE OK TO MOVE THE A/C FROM SPOT 2 TO THE CENTERLINE OF THE RAMP AT BLDG 151.  THE A/C WAS MOVED TO 0610 L AND CARGO LOADING/FUELING WAS RESUMED BY 0615 L.  BOTH CARGO LOADING WAS COMPLETED AT 0650 L AND FUELING WAS COMPLETED AT 0715 L.  DUE TO THE AMOUNT OF TIME TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL THE PA POLICE WOULD NOT LET US MOVE THE A/C.  THE CREW STAYED O/B AND WE WERE FINALLY ABLE TO DEPART AT 0820 L.  THERE WAS NO DAMAGE TO THE AIRCRAFT AND NO INJURIES TO ANY LOADING PERSONNEL.
IT APPEARED TO HAVE FALLEN OVER IN THE TRUCK AND WHEN THEY OPENED THE DOOR IT WAS LEAKING THE PRODUCT WAS RECOVERED IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED
