THE BOX HAD A CONSIDERABLE AMOUNT OF CONDENSATION ON IT.  OUR COURIER HAD TALKED TO THE SHIPPER IN THE PAST ABOUT SHIPPING DRY ICE ON THEIR PRODUCT.  HE WAS ASSURED BY THE SHIPPER THAT THEY DID NOT USE DRY ICE.  THIS EVENING, BASED UPON THE CONDENSATION THE DECISION WAS MADE TO OPEN THE TWO BOXES.  THERE WAS A BAG INSIDE THE BOX WAS CLEARLY STATED DRY ICE.  BASED UPON THE NATURE OF DRY ICE AND THAT IT QUICKLY DISSAPATES, I ASKED LOCAL FEDEX EMPLOYEES TO TAKE PICTURES OF THE SIX SIDES OF THE BOX AND THE CONTENTS.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS, EMERGENCY RESPONSE INFORMATION TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED.  I SPOKE TO THE SHIPPER'S COMPANY, SPECIFICALLY STEVE BASS, THE DC MGR. STEVE INDICATED THAT HE'S NEVER HAD ISSUES SHIPPING IN THE PAST WITH ONE OF OUR COMPETITORS.  HE ALSO DECLINED TO INDICATE IF HIS EMPLOYEES WERE TRAINED TO SHIP DANGEROUS GOODS.  THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED, I SPOKE TO SA LYNNETTE HURM, FAA IN LOUISVILLE.  THE FREIGHT WAS RELEASED AFTER DIGITAL PICTURES WERE TAKEN OF THE FREIGHT.

JENSEN REPORTED HE HAD SPOKEN TO THE SHIPPER AND DISCOVERED THE PRODUCT, CHLORPROPHAM, A HAZARDOUS SOLID, MELTS INTO A LIQUID AT NINETY THREE DEGREES FAHRENHEIT. MR. JENSEN STATED THE PRODUCT RE-STABILIZED AT LOWER TEMPERATURES AND THEY WERE LOOKING AT WAYS TO REMEDIATE THE PRODUCT ALREADY ON THE GROUND. MR. JENSEN CONTACTED THE TRUCKING COMPANY, TASKED WITH SHIPPING THE PRODUCT TO BILLINGS, MONTANA, TO DETERMINE THE NEXESSARY STEPS TO TAKE IN PREPARATION OF TRUCKING THE PRODUCT.  ON 09/08/2005 AT 11:45 AM, JENSEN REPORTED THE PRODUCT HAD BEGUN TO LEAK AGAIN DURING THE NIGHT AND THE TRUCKING COMPANY REFUSED TO TRANSPORT. MR. JENSEN STATED THE LEAK HAD STOPPED AND THE PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED INTO FIFTY FIVE GALLON DRUMS.  ON 09/10/2005 AT 10:53 AM, MGR. JENSEN ADVISED THAT THE PRODUCT HAD BEEN OVERPACKED INTO 196 STEEL DRUMS. HALF OF THE SHIPMENT REMAINED IN THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER AND THE OTHER HALF WAS TRANSLOADED INTO CONTAINER HJCU 753568. MR. JENSEN STATED THE CONTAINERS WERE RELEASED TO UW TRANSPORTATION AT 03:30 PM ON 09/09/05 FOR TRANSPORTATION TO DESTINATION.

UPRR S RESPONSE MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATIONS CENTER NOTIFIED LANE SEKAVEC, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY OF AN ODOR OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA IN THE 18TH STREET YRAD, KANSAS CITY, KS. MR. SEKAVEC PROCEEDED TO THE AREA AND NARROWED THE LOCATION DOWN TO NORTH 16 TRACK. A CUT OF SIX ANHYDROUS AMMONIA CARS WAS FOUND IN THE TRACK AND UTLX 80787 WAS DETERMINED TO BE THE CAR LEAKING PRODUCT. A CHECK OF THE CAR FOUND THE LEAK ORIGINATING FROM THE SAMPLE LINE PIPE NIPPLE AT THE PRESSURE PLATE. AN ATTEMPT TO TIGHTEN THE NIPPLE WAS NOT SUCCESSFUL AND MR. SEKAVEC DECIDED TO CAP THE LEAK WITH A MIDLAND CAPPING KIT. HAZMAT RESPONSE (CONTRACTOR) WAS CONTACTED TO RESPOND WITH THE KIT AND APPLY IT TO THE CAR. AFTER CAPPING THE DEFECTIVE VALVE, THE CAR WAS SECURED IN TRACK 16 UNTIL IT COULD BE ACCOMPANIED DURING MOVEMENT TO ANOTHER TRACK IN THE YARD FOR TRANSLOAD.  DURING THE RELEASE, MR. SEKAVEC HAD BEEN IN CONVERSATION WITH PERSONNEL FROM MARTIN RESOURCES AND CONTINENTAL NITROGEN, SHIPPER AND LESSOR OF THE TANK CAR. DEAN DRENT WITH CONTINENTAL NITROGEN WAS ADVISED THE PRODUCT WOULD NEED TO BE TRANSFERRED TO TANK TRUCKS OR ANOTHER TANK CAR SINCE UTLX 80787 WAS NOT ABLE TO BE MOVED WITH THE MIDLAND KIT IN PLACE AND THERE WAS NO OTHER WAY TO REPAIR THE LEAKING PIPE NIPPLE.  ON SEPTEMBER 16, MIKE KELLY, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, MR. SEKAVEC AND HAZ-MAT RESPONSE (CONTRACTOR) TRANSFERRED THE CARS CONTENTS INTO FOUR TANK TRUCKS PROVIDED BY CONTINENTAL NITROGEN. THE REMAINING VAPOR WAS BUBBLED OFF INTO APPROXIMATELY 6000 GALLONS OF WATER, FORMING AQUA AMMONIA FERTILIZER THAT WAS TAKEN BY A FARMER IN LOUISBURG, KS.   MR. SEKAVEC REMOVED THE DEFECTIVE PIPE NIPPLE AND SAMPLE VALVE FROM THE TANK CAR AND REPLACED IT WITH A BOILER PLUG TO SECURE THE CAR FOR TRANSPORTATION. AN FRA ONE TIME MOVEMENT APPROVAL (FRA- 05100262) WAS OBTAINED ON BEHALF OF CONTINENTAL NITROGEN TO MOVE THE CAR TO MARION, OH, FOR DISPOSITION.  NO REMEDIATION WAS NEEDED DUE TO THE RELEASE BEING A VAPOR, CAUSING NO CONTAMINATION OF THE AREA.

column168: DOUG BRUECK, TRAIN MASTER, REPORTED A SMALL LEAK COMING FROM THE BOTTOM OF TANKCAR GATX 6573 WHICH WAS LOCATED IN THE ALTON SOUTHERN YARD IN EAST ST. LOUIS, IL.  MR. BRUECK ADVISED THERE WERE NO INJURIES, FIRES, NOR DERAILMENT INVOLVED IN THE INCIDENT.  JOHN MILLER, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED AND A CONFERENCE CALL WAS ESTABLISHED WITH MR. BRUECK.  MR. BRUECK ADVISED THE LEAK WAS ACTUALLY COMING FROM THE TOP OF THE TANKCAR AND WAS ISOLATED TO THE TOP OF THE TANKCAR ONLY WITH NO PRODUCT REACHING THE GROUND.  MR. BRUECK ADVISED RICHARD WULFF, MECHANICAL SUPERINTENDENT, WAS INSPECTING THE TANKCAR AND WOULD HAVE MORE DETAILED.  MR. WULFF WAS CONTACTED AND ADDED TO THE CONFERENCE CALL.  MR. WULFF ADVISED HE WAS UNSURE IF THE MATERIAL ON THE TANKCAR WAS PRODUCT THAT HAD LEAKED, OR IF IT WAS CONDENSATION FORMING ON THE TANKCAR.  MR. MILLER ADVISED TO CONTACT KIESEL COMPANY, ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR, AND HAVE THEM INSPECT THE TANKCAR, RUN A PH TEST TO IDENTIFY THE MATERIAL, AS WELL AS HELP ANY REMEDIATION DEEMED NECESSARY.  ALL STATE AND FEDERAL NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE.  AT 09:53 PM, MILLER ADVISED KIESEL PERSONNEL DETERMINED THAT THE LEAK WAS THE RESULT OF A RUPTURED DISK.  KIESEL PERSONNEL DID NOT HAVE THE CORRECT REPLACEMENT PART BUT MR. MILLER DID.  AT 12:52 AM, MR. MILLER REPORTED THAT THE TANKCAR HAD BEEN REPAIRED AND CLEANED AND RELEASED TO THE TRANSPORTATION DEPARTMENT.  NO PRODUCT REACHED THE GROUND.

LERCH HAD THE CAR SET OUT FOR FURTHER INSPECTION DURING DAYLIGHT HOURS THE FOLLOWING MORNING.  AT 07:20 AM ON 09/30/05 MGR. LERCH REINSPECTED CAR AND RELEASED IT FOR TRANSPORTATION WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  THERE WERE NO DRAINS, WATERWAYS IMPACTED OR REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE. column168: AT 0115HRS ON 09/15/05, FRANK LERCH, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY RESPONDED TO A TRAIN VS TRAIN HEAD ON COLLISION/DERAILMENT INVOLVING TRAINS LEF52-14 AND MPBSR-13 LOCATED AT SHEPHERD, TX., MILEPOST 55.1, LUFKIN SUBDIVISION.  INITIAL REPORTS INDICATED THERE HAD BEEN A RELEASE OF DIESEL FUEL AND POSSIBLE RELEASE OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  WHILE ENROUTE TO THE SCENE, MGR. LERCH DISPATCHED USES ENVIRONMENTAL, EAGLE CONSTRUCTION ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTORS TO ASSIST, AND CTEH (CENTER FOR TOXICOLOGY & ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH) TO CONDUCT AIR MONITORING.  ON ARRIVAL, MGR. LERCH WAS ADVISED THAT AN EVACUATION ORDER OF THE SURROUNDING AREA WAS IN PLACE.  THE EVACUATION ORDER WAS LIFTED AT APPROXIMATELY 0615HRS.  COUNTY ROAD #150 AND LOOP 424 WERE BLOCKED OR PARTIALLY BLOCKED FOR APPROXIMATELY 12 HOURS.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE DERAILMENT SITE THE FOLLOWING WAS OBSERVED.  TRAIN LEF52-14 WAS NOTED WITH 1 UNIT, UP 1385 DERAILED ON ITS SIDE, WITH APPROXIMATELY 3000 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL AND CRANK CASE OIL RELEASED, AND CONTAINED IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA.  TRAIN MPBSR-13 WAS NOTED WITH 3 UNITS DERAILED, NS 9669 DERAILED ON ITS SIDE WITH APPROXIMATELY 3000 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL AND CRANKCASE OIL RELEASED AND CONTAINED IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA.  UPON INSPECTION OF ALL CARS, CAR SCMX 4334, RESIDUE EMPTY LAST CONTAINING METHYL ISOBUTYL KETONE WAS NOTED TO HAVE BEEN PUNCTURED, AND HAD RELEASED RESIDUE VAPOR INTO THE AIR.  ALL OTHER CARS WERE DAMAGED, BUT WERE NOT BREACHED.  THE AREA WAS MONITORED, AND AFTER DETERMINING THERE WERE NO FIRE OR HEALTH HAZARDS, WRECKING, OR CLEARING OF THE CARS BEGAN.  GEOFF REEDER, MANAGER OF SITE REMEDIATION OVERSAW THE CLEAN-UP AND RECOVERY OF RELEASED DIESEL FUEL AND OIL, FRANK LERCH, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION AND TIM O'BRIEN, REGIONAL MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY OVER SAW THE HANDLING AND CLEARING OF THE DAMAGED EMPTY HAZARDOUS CARS.  WHILE WRECKING CREWS WERE MOVING BREACHED CAR SCMX 4334, APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  PRODUCT WAS IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED AND RECOVERED VIA EXCAVATION BY ON SITE EMERGENCY CONTRACTORS.  THERE WERE NO DRAINS, WATERWAYS IMPACTED OR REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE.  AT 1915 HRS THE MAINLINE TRACK WAS PLACED BACK INTO SERVICE WITH ALL DERAILED CARS HAVING BEEN CLEARED.  DAMAGED TANK CARS WERE TRUCKED TO THE ENGLEWOOD TRAIN YARD FOR FURTHER HANDLING.  DAMAGED LOCOMOTIVES THAT WERE ABLE TO BE RERAILED, WERE PULLED TO THE SETTEGAST LOCOMOTIVE FACILITY.  LOCOMOTIVES THAT COULD NOT BE RERAILED, WERE LOADED ONTO SPECIAL LOWBOY FLAT TRAILER AND TRUCKED TO THE SETTEGAST FACILITY.  DURING THE WEEK OF 10-3-05, ALL CARS WERE CLEANED AND PURGED OF ANY RESIDUE PRODUCT FOR FURTHER HANDLING.  TANK CAR FLMX 17103, RESIDUE EMPTY LAST CONTAINING HYDROGEN PEROXIDE WAS CLEANED AND PURGED AT THE DERAILMENT SITE.  TANK CAR UTLX 802873, RESIDUE EMPTY LAST CONTAINING ETHYLENE OXIDE WAS LOADED ON A HOSPITAL FLATCAR AND TRANSPORTED TO LYONDELL EQUISTAR FOR CLEANING AND PURGING

column42: SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE, SOLUTION, WITH 16 PERCENT OR MORE AVAILABLE CHLORINE
column168: ON SEPTEMBER 13, 2005 AT APPROXIMATELY 9:00 AM, DAVID DOBRANSKY WAS TRAVELING SOUTHBOUND ON BAILEY ROAD IN SAN JOSE, CALIFORNIA WHEN HE LOST CONTROL OF HIS TRACTOR TRAILER AND CRASHED THE UNIT ON BAILEY ROAD.  BILL JONES WAS CONTACTED AT APPROXIMATELY 9:30 AM BY RAY STORMS OF THE SAN JOSE FIRE DEPARTMENT WHO WAS THE INCIDENT COMMANDER ON THE SCENE.  MR. STORMS INFORMED BCS THAT MR. DOBRANSKY HAD CRASHED HIS TRACTOR TRAILER UNIT ON BAILEY ROAD AND HAD BEEN AIR LIFTED TO A LOCAL HOSPITAL.  MR. STORMS ALSO INFORMED BCS THAT A SMALL LEAK HAD OCCURRED IN THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER AND SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE WAS DRIPPING ONTO THE GROUND.  BCS ASKED MR. STORMS HOW MUCH PRODUCT WAS ON THE TRAILER AND WAS TOLD THAT APPROXIMATELY 3091 GALLONS OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE STILL REMAINED ON THE TRAILER.  THIS INFORMATION WAS OBTAINED BY MR. STORMS FROM MR. DOBRANSKY'S TANK INVENTORY SHEET.  BCS TOLD MR. STORMS THAT WE WOULD HAVE AN EMPTY TANKER TRAILER AND RESPONSE TEAM ON THE SCENE TO EMPTY MR. DOBRANKY'S TRAILER AND HELP WITH THE CLEANUP OF THE INCIDENT.  BCS IMMEDIATELY PUT TOGETHER A RESPONSE TEAM FOR THE INCIDENT.  STEVE TOCCALINO, MATT MILLER AND ED PRATT RESPONDED WITH BOTH MAINTENANCE TRUCKS WITH SPILL KITS, HOSES, PUMPS AND ANY OTHER EQUIPMENT NEEDED TO EMPTY THE LEAKING TRAILER.  TOM CARDELLI WAS IN THE RWC YARD AT THE TIME OF ANY OTHER EQUIPMENT NEEDED TO EMPTY THE LEAKING TRAILER.  TOM CARDELLI WAS IN THE RWC YARD AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT AND WAS INSTRUCTED TO WASH OUT RUBBER LINED TRAILER 42 AND DRIVE IT TO THE SCENE.  BILL JONES, MARK SHEFFIELD, LARRY HULSE AND CHRIS SHORES ALSO RESPONDED TO THE ACCIDENT SCENE.  WHEN BILL, MARK, LARRY AND CHRIS ARRIVED AT THE SCENE, WE MET WITH MR. STORMS TO ACCESS THE ACCIDENT SCENE.  THE TRACTOR TRAILER UNIT WAS APPROXIMATELY 10 FEET OFF OF BAILEY ROAD ON THE DRIVER'S SIDE OF THE UNIT.  MR. STORMS HAD DISPATCHED TWO TOW TRUCKS TO THE SCENE THAT HAD SECURED THE TRACTOR TRAILER TO PREVENT IT FROM SHIFTING AND ROLLING DOWN A HILL OF APPROXIMATELY 50 FEET.  THE ACCIDENT SCENE WAS SECURED BY THE SAN JOSE FIRE DEPARTMENT WHEN WE ARRIVED.  STEVE, MATT, AND ED ARRIVED AT SCENE APPROXIMATELY 20 MINUTES LATER AND WE MET WITH MR. STORMS TO DETERMINE AN ACTION PLAN FOR EMPTYING THE LEAKING TRAILER OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE.  SINCE THE TANKER TRAILER WAS APPROXIMATELY TWO THIRDS FULL, WE DETERMINED THAT THE SAFEST WAY TO TRANSFER THE PRODUCT WAS TO CUT A HOLE IN THE VAPOR SPACE OF THE TRAILER AND PLACE A STINGER INTO THE HOLE AND BEGIN TRANSFERRING PRODUCT.  AS WE CONTINUED TO EMPTY PRODUCT FROM THE LEAKING TANKER TRAILER, WE CONTINUED TO CUT HOLES IN THE VAPOR SPACE OF THE TANKER UNTIL ALL THE PRODUCT WAS REMOVED.  THE LEAKING TANKER TRAILER WAS ON A SLIGHT DOWNHILL FACING THE TRACTOR.  THE FIRST HOLE WAS CUT AT THE BACK OF THE TRAILER IN THE VAPOR SPACE AND AS PRODUCT WAS REMOVED, WE CONTINUE TO CUT HOLES TOWARD THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER UNTIL ALL PRODUCT WAS REMOVED.  IT TOOK APPROXIMATELY 3 HOURS TO REMOVE ALL THE PRODUCT FROM TH
column169: ON WEDNESDAY, SEPTEMBER 14, 2005 WE HELD A SAFETY MEETING AT THE REDWOOD CITY BRANCH TO DISCUSS THE INCIDENT WITH DAVE DOBRANSKY.  WE ALSO INCORPORATED A ROLLOVER TRAINING PROGRAM FOR OUR DRIVERS AND FOR THE ENTIRE COMPANY.  THIS TRAINING WAS GIVEN AS THE OCTOBER SAFETY TRAINING FOR BCS.  THE TRAINING INCLUDED A VIDEO AND POWERPOINT PRESENTATION.  WE TALK ABOUT SAFETY INCIDENTS AT EVERY SAFETY MEETING, WHICH ARE HELD ONCE PER MONTH.  THIS INCIDENT WILL BE DISCUSSED AT EVERY SAFETY MEETING THROUGH THE YEAR 2006.  WE WILL ALSO HAVE ROLLOVER SAFETY TRAINING AGAIN AS ONE OF THE SAFETY TOPICS IN 2006.  WE HOPE THIS KEEPS OUR AWARENESS OF THIS TYPE OF INCIDENT UP AND PREVENTS FUTURE OCCURRENCES.

column168: RAILCAR OF ASPHALT ARRIVED AT THE TERMINAL. OPERATOR CLIMBED ON TOP OF CAR AND VERIFIED THAT DISCHARGE VALVE WAS CLOSED. THE CAP ON THE DISCHARGE LINE WAS REMOVED.  EVIDENTLY THE VALVE WAS OPEN - THE OPERATOR THOUGHT IT WAS CLOSED WHEN HE TESTED IT AS THERE WAS A PLUG OF HARDENED ASPHALT PREVENTING THE VALVE FROM BEING CLOSED WHEN THE CAR WAS LOADED. WHEN THE DISCHARGE LINE CAP WAS REMOVED, HOT ASPHALT PUSHED OUT THE PLUG OF HARDENED MATERIAL.  APPROX 1000 GALLONS ESCAPED BEFORE THE INJURED OPERATOR (BURN TO ARM FROM SPLASHED ASPHALT) WAS ABLE TO GET BACK ON TOP OF THE CAR & SHUT VALVE.
column169: NO CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TAKEN.

column168: TECO EXPRESS, IENC.   P.O. BOX 551416   11999 PLANO ROAD, STE 154   DALLAS, TEXAS 75243   (214) 570-9522   SEPTEMBER 14, 2005   TO WHOM IT MAY CONCERN:   SUBJECT: INTERIM REPORT OF PEPSI COLA CHEMICAL SPILL INCIDENT OF 9/14/05, DRIVER MICHAEL HOOD, TX LICENSE 20884762, IN VEHICLE #19, 1996 INTERNATIONAL BOBTAIL, VIN TH265620. THE INCIDENT HAPPENED AT APPROXIMATELY 12:35PM ON THE 14TH OF SEPTEMBER AT THE PEPSI COLA PLANT LOCATED AT 4532 HIGHWAY 67 IN MESQUITE, TEXAS 75150. OUR DRIVER, MICHAEL HOOD, WAS ATTEMPTING TO MAKE A DELIVERY OF FOUR DRUMS (ECOLAB BILL OF LADMG 400-7939053) AND WAS INFORMED BY A PEPSI COLA EMPLOYEE AS HE GOT TO THEIR GUARD SHACK THAT SOMETHING WAS SPILLING FROM HIS TRUCK. THE EMPLOYEE WAS STANDING APPROXIMATELY 15 FEET FROM THE PASSENGER SIDE FRONT OF THE TRUCK. OUR DRIVER NOTICED ONE ADDITIONAL EMPLOYEE APPROACHING THE TRUCK AS HE WAS GETTING OUR INVESTIGATING, AND THEN BOTH EMPLOYEES LEFT THE IMMEDIATE AREA. IT WAS LATER LEARNED THAT ONE OF THOSE MENTIONED EMPLOYEES TOLD SOMEONE THAT SHE HAD BEEN SPLASHED WITH THE CHEMICAL; HOWEVER OUR DRIVER HAS STATED TO ME THAT SHE WAS NO WHERE NEAR THE SPLASH AREA OF THE CHEMICAL, BUT MEDICAL PERSONNEL WERE CALLED IN AND I’M SURE WILL BE ABLE TO DETERMINE THAT. MICHAEL HOOD OPENED THE REAR DOOR AND NOTICED THAT TWO OF THE FOUR DRUMS HAD FALLEN OFF OF THE PALLET (THE PALLET WAS SHRINK WRAPPED, BUT NOT TIED DOWN INSIDE THE TRUCK AS IS OUR REQUIREMENT. ONCE HE GOT INTO THE BACK OF THE TRUCK, THE FUMES WERE TOO SEVERE FOR HIM TO CONTINUE THE INVESTIGATION. HE THEN EXITED THE TRUCK AND CLOSED THE DOOR AND IMMEDIATELY CALLED ME.     THEIR WAS NO WAY OF KNOWING WHAT CHEMICAL WAS LEAKING AT THAT TIME, SO I CALLED DENNIS MURRAY TO DETERMINE THE HAZARD INVOLVED WITH ALL THREE ITEM CODES ON THE PALLET. DENNIS FAXED ME MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEETS (MSDS) ON ALL CODE NUMBERS AND I FAXED THE SAME TO PEPSI COLA. THE ITEM CODES ARE TWO (2) 54 GAL. DRUMS OF AC-30 CODE #47449, ONE (1) 50 GAL. DRUM OF BEVRO-SHEEN CODE #43943, AND ONE (1) 50 GAL. DRUM OF VORTEXX CODE # 43841. IT WAS NOW APPROXIMATELY 1:30PM AND I WAS INFORMED THAT THE ENTRANCE TO THE PLANT HAD BEEN CLOSED BY THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THAT NO DETERMINATION AS TO WHAT WAS LEAKING HAD OCCURRED. I CALLED AND TALKED WITH STAN HATFIELD AND THE SAFETY MANAGER AT THE ECOLAB PLANT TO ASCERTAIN THE CLEAN-UP PROCEDURES FOR EACH CODE NUMBER LISTED SINCE WE STILL DID NOT KNOW. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD QUARANTINED THE TRUCK AND SURROUNDING AREA BY THIS TIME AND WAS NOT ALLOWING ANYONE TO COME NEAR THE VEHICLE. THE DALLAS HAZMAT RESPONSE TEAM WAS THEN SUITING UP WITH HAZMAT SUITS AND SELF CONTAINED BREATHING APPARATUS (SCBA) TO DETERMINE WHAT WAS LEAKING. THEY HAD ALSO SHUT DOWN THE SOUTHBOUND ENTRANCE TO BIG TOWN BOULEVARD AND BIG TOWN BOULEVARD ALSO. I WAS INFORMED BY STAN HATFIELD AND THE SAFETY MANAGER THAT IF THERE WAS NOT A REALLY STRONG VINEGAR ODOR, WE COULD BE SURE THAT THE VORTEXX WAS NOT LEAKING, AND THAT THE CLEAN-UP CONSISTED OF ABSORBENTS.
